00:03:58.250 --> 00:04:01.280
It's about being able to
work through problem-solving

00:04:01.280 --> 00:04:04.850
and how to have a meaningful
connection with another person.

00:04:04.850 --> 00:04:06.090
OK.

00:04:06.090 --> 00:04:10.220
So what I'd like to
start out by doing

00:04:10.220 --> 00:04:13.440
is to just give you
a brief synopsis

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:16.260
as far as Dr. Gottman's
research and how

00:04:16.260 --> 00:04:19.660
he came to come about
all of this information.

00:04:19.660 --> 00:04:21.940
So Dr. Gottman
originally started out

00:04:21.940 --> 00:04:24.800
as a mathematics major at MIT.

00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:27.170
And he was actually
young when he started.

00:04:27.170 --> 00:04:28.220
But he had a roommate.

00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:30.990
And this roommate was
studying psychology.

00:04:30.990 --> 00:04:33.570
And I don't know how many
of you enjoy psychology,

00:04:33.570 --> 00:04:35.769
but John was looking
at his math books

00:04:35.769 --> 00:04:38.060
and had decided that whatever
his roommate was studying

00:04:38.060 --> 00:04:42.280
was more fun than what he was
studying, which I don't blame.

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:44.750
So he promptly finished
up his mathematics degree

00:04:44.750 --> 00:04:46.790
and then went in to
become a psychologist.

00:04:46.790 --> 00:04:50.980
So not only does he have this
firm foundation in numbers,

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:52.900
he became a
researcher, but he also

00:04:52.900 --> 00:04:54.910
has this firm foundation
in psychology.

00:04:54.910 --> 00:04:58.520
So we have this amazing
combination in this math wizard

00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:00.430
that was interested
in relationships

00:05:00.430 --> 00:05:03.140
but could also study
really, really well

00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:06.460
and definitively defining
what it is that relationships,

00:05:06.460 --> 00:05:08.280
makes them work.

00:05:08.280 --> 00:05:12.120
So Dr. Gottman went from
MIT, and then he went over

00:05:12.120 --> 00:05:13.850
to the University of Indiana.

00:05:13.850 --> 00:05:18.510
And he started working with
his best friend, Bob Levinson.

00:05:18.510 --> 00:05:22.070
So Dr. Gottman says at the time
that his relationships were not

00:05:22.070 --> 00:05:23.320
going so hot at the time.

00:05:23.320 --> 00:05:26.990
And Bob Levinson and
him were interested in

00:05:26.990 --> 00:05:28.910
good relationships with women.

00:05:28.910 --> 00:05:30.600
But at the time, Bob
said, we can either

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:33.900
research good relationships
or we can have them.

00:05:33.900 --> 00:05:35.630
And right now,
we're researchers.

00:05:35.630 --> 00:05:39.250
So the two of them set
out to discover in,

00:05:39.250 --> 00:05:42.220
I think he would say somewhat of
a selfish way, what is it that

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:44.660
makes good relationships work.

00:05:44.660 --> 00:05:46.380
And they wanted to
study relationships

00:05:46.380 --> 00:05:48.390
in a way that had
never been done before.

00:05:48.390 --> 00:05:52.880
It's very difficult to predict
behavior in one person.

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:55.040
But Dr. Gottman wanted
to predict behavior

00:05:55.040 --> 00:05:56.790
with two people.

00:05:56.790 --> 00:06:00.650
So they would bring couples
in to a laboratory setting

00:06:00.650 --> 00:06:04.830
and within eight hours of
the couple being apart,

00:06:04.830 --> 00:06:07.190
he would have the two of
them sit side by side.

00:06:07.190 --> 00:06:10.670
And they would hook
them up to monitors

00:06:10.670 --> 00:06:12.580
that would study how
fast their hearts were

00:06:12.580 --> 00:06:13.920
beating at the time.

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:16.520
They would see how much they
were sweating by testing

00:06:16.520 --> 00:06:19.170
the palms of their hands.

00:06:19.170 --> 00:06:22.016
They had monitors underneath
the chairs that would measure

00:06:22.016 --> 00:06:23.140
how much they would fidget.

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:25.810
They were called jiggle-ometers.

00:06:25.810 --> 00:06:27.900
And then he would just
ask for these couples,

00:06:27.900 --> 00:06:30.100
I simply want for
you to just catch up.

00:06:30.100 --> 00:06:32.020
Tell me about your day.

00:06:32.020 --> 00:06:33.270
What have you been doing?

00:06:33.270 --> 00:06:34.775
So couples would
turn to one another

00:06:34.775 --> 00:06:36.400
and they would start
talking about sort

00:06:36.400 --> 00:06:38.710
of the mundane things
about their day.

00:06:38.710 --> 00:06:40.450
Meanwhile, researchers
were coding

00:06:40.450 --> 00:06:42.160
their facial expressions.

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:44.800
They had cameras that
were recording them.

00:06:44.800 --> 00:06:46.610
And back in the
day, in the '70s,

00:06:46.610 --> 00:06:49.500
how large was the computer
back in the '70s, right?

00:06:49.500 --> 00:06:51.000
Size of a refrigerator.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:52.820
All that computer
was intended to do

00:06:52.820 --> 00:06:54.540
was to take the
physiological data that

00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:58.140
was going on with these
couples and timecode it.

00:06:58.140 --> 00:07:00.800
And then he would ask for
couples to switch over.

00:07:00.800 --> 00:07:02.740
I want you to just
choose a topic.

00:07:02.740 --> 00:07:04.500
Something that the
two of you haven't

00:07:04.500 --> 00:07:05.650
been able to agree upon.

00:07:05.650 --> 00:07:07.900
And I just want you to
try to solve the problem.

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:11.775
Have this conflict conversation
while we are watching you.

00:07:11.775 --> 00:07:13.614
So couples start
to pick a problem.

00:07:13.614 --> 00:07:15.530
Maybe they're talking
about the mother-in-law,

00:07:15.530 --> 00:07:17.180
maybe they're talking
about laundry.

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:19.580
What are things that get
underneath your skin?

00:07:19.580 --> 00:07:21.520
And they recorded the data.

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:23.980
So they had these
two snippets of time.

00:07:23.980 --> 00:07:27.340
Happy conversation, not
so happy conversation.

00:07:27.340 --> 00:07:29.130
Then they sent the couples away.

00:07:29.130 --> 00:07:31.140
All they were looking
for were patterns.

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:32.660
They really didn't
have a hypothesis

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:34.570
at the time of what
they were looking for,

00:07:34.570 --> 00:07:36.954
but they were looking
for patterns a lot

00:07:36.954 --> 00:07:39.370
like early day astronomers
that were looking at the stars.

00:07:39.370 --> 00:07:42.740
Simply looking for something
to stick out to them.

00:07:42.740 --> 00:07:44.440
That was about 35 years ago.

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:47.380
25 years ago, he goes from
the University of Indiana,

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:49.770
now he's at the
University of Washington.

00:07:49.770 --> 00:07:52.970
And he opens up what
he calls the Love Lab.

00:07:52.970 --> 00:07:56.520
The BBC had sort of
called it the Love Lab.

00:07:56.520 --> 00:07:58.340
But what he wanted
to do was he wanted

00:07:58.340 --> 00:08:01.760
to see if couples were in a
natural environment for 24

00:08:01.760 --> 00:08:03.290
hours, what would I see.

00:08:03.290 --> 00:08:04.210
What would stick out?

00:08:04.210 --> 00:08:05.840
What patterns would arise?

00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:10.750
So he made this one bedroom
studio apartment as comfortable

00:08:10.750 --> 00:08:13.840
as possible on the University
of Washington's campus.

00:08:13.840 --> 00:08:16.070
It overlooked the
Montlake Cut, so you could

00:08:16.070 --> 00:08:17.430
see the boats floating by.

00:08:17.430 --> 00:08:19.080
It was a beautiful setting.

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:21.710
And he would say from Sunday
at 8 o'clock in the morning

00:08:21.710 --> 00:08:24.110
until Monday morning at
8 o'clock in the morning,

00:08:24.110 --> 00:08:26.180
I want you to just
come and hang out.

00:08:26.180 --> 00:08:27.680
We will not prompt you.

00:08:27.680 --> 00:08:29.890
We're not going to give
you anything to do.

00:08:29.890 --> 00:08:32.700
We just simply want to
watch and observe you.

00:08:32.700 --> 00:08:35.867
But we want this to be, like,
really comfortable for you.

00:08:35.867 --> 00:08:38.200
We want you to feel as if
you're in a bed and breakfast.

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:40.820
We want this to be as
natural as possible.

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:42.880
So couples would bring
their creature comforts.

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:46.172
They would bring groceries,
they would bring newspapers,

00:08:46.172 --> 00:08:48.380
they would bring
puzzles and games.

00:08:48.380 --> 00:08:50.340
Anything they could
do for 24 hours.

00:08:50.340 --> 00:08:53.040
So in this bed and
breakfast-like setting,

00:08:53.040 --> 00:08:55.064
couples would hang out.

00:08:55.064 --> 00:08:56.480
Again, they're
wearing the monitor

00:08:56.480 --> 00:09:02.030
so that they could see how
fast their heart was beating.

00:09:02.030 --> 00:09:05.686
Any time that they urinated,
they would take urine samples.

00:09:05.686 --> 00:09:07.880
They had a one-way
mirror where researchers

00:09:07.880 --> 00:09:11.330
would be back behind coding
their facial expressions.

00:09:11.330 --> 00:09:12.946
And when everything
was said and done,

00:09:12.946 --> 00:09:14.570
they would go right
next door, and they

00:09:14.570 --> 00:09:15.780
would have their blood drawn.

00:09:15.780 --> 00:09:18.690
But Dr. Gottman assures us
that it was very relaxing

00:09:18.690 --> 00:09:24.512
for couples and it was a lot
like a bed and breakfast.

00:09:24.512 --> 00:09:26.660
So then he would send
these couples home.

00:09:26.660 --> 00:09:28.690
But it was a longitudinal study.

00:09:28.690 --> 00:09:31.470
So meanwhile, he's
collecting all of this data,

00:09:31.470 --> 00:09:33.209
and he's starting to
look for patterns.

00:09:33.209 --> 00:09:35.000
The only way that you
can look for patterns

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:36.910
is if you have this
longitudinal data.

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:38.390
Where do these couples end up?

00:09:38.390 --> 00:09:40.890
What do we know
about these couples?

00:09:40.890 --> 00:09:44.350
So he had 147 newlywed couples.

00:09:44.350 --> 00:09:46.690
And then he checked back in
with those newlywed couples.

00:09:46.690 --> 00:09:51.620
Of those newlywed couples, 17
of them ended up divorcing.

00:09:51.620 --> 00:09:53.310
What were the patterns?

00:09:53.310 --> 00:09:56.570
How do we know what is distinct
and different about the 130

00:09:56.570 --> 00:09:58.590
couples that stayed
together and what

00:09:58.590 --> 00:10:00.940
is distinct and different
about the 17 couples that

00:10:00.940 --> 00:10:02.320
ended up divorcing?

00:10:02.320 --> 00:10:05.830
So remember when I said that
he was very interested in being

00:10:05.830 --> 00:10:08.050
able to predict behavior.

00:10:08.050 --> 00:10:10.610
So it's hard to predict
behavior for two people.

00:10:10.610 --> 00:10:13.380
Even more difficult
than one person.

00:10:13.380 --> 00:10:16.750
He was able to predict 15
out of 17 of those couples.

00:10:16.750 --> 00:10:19.720
So he said those, those, those,
those, those, those, those.

00:10:19.720 --> 00:10:22.360
And when he checked back in
with the couples, 15 out of 17.

00:10:22.360 --> 00:10:26.000
So with 90% and above
accuracy, that those couples

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:27.520
would end up divorcing.

00:10:27.520 --> 00:10:29.530
And he repeated this
study seven times

00:10:29.530 --> 00:10:32.550
and still was able to
predict with 90% accuracy.

00:10:32.550 --> 00:10:34.710
So we know with
pretty good certainty

00:10:34.710 --> 00:10:36.360
what those behaviors are.

00:10:36.360 --> 00:10:38.480
Are you interested
in knowing what it is

00:10:38.480 --> 00:10:40.022
that those couples were doing?

00:10:40.022 --> 00:10:42.480
Either the ones that weren't
doing so hot and the ones that

00:10:42.480 --> 00:10:43.620
were doing well?

00:10:43.620 --> 00:10:44.580
OK.

00:10:44.580 --> 00:10:46.610
So that is the
foundation of this book.

00:10:46.610 --> 00:10:49.450
And John jokes that he's
really just a researcher,

00:10:49.450 --> 00:10:52.210
he wasn't very interested
in helping couples.

00:10:52.210 --> 00:10:54.830
He was making a fine living
at watching these couples'

00:10:54.830 --> 00:10:56.710
relationships deteriorate.

00:10:56.710 --> 00:10:58.370
It wasn't without
the bleeding heart

00:10:58.370 --> 00:11:01.310
of his beautiful, wonderful
wife, Dr. Julie Schwartz

00:11:01.310 --> 00:11:04.260
Gottman, that really got him
interested in taking this data

00:11:04.260 --> 00:11:06.890
and turning it into
something that real couples

00:11:06.890 --> 00:11:08.460
could hold onto.

00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:11.130
So that is how the "Seven
Principles" book came to be,

00:11:11.130 --> 00:11:13.160
is they started
working with couples

00:11:13.160 --> 00:11:15.850
and applying the concepts
that he had learned.

00:11:15.850 --> 00:11:18.910
And says, don't do
this, but do this.

00:11:18.910 --> 00:11:21.180
And that's how the "Seven
Principles" book came to be.

00:11:21.180 --> 00:11:26.857
So without further ado, I'm
really not good at slideshows.

00:11:26.857 --> 00:11:28.440
This is really just
because my husband

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:31.520
told me to do a slideshow.

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:32.220
I listen.

00:11:32.220 --> 00:11:32.790
I listen.

00:11:32.790 --> 00:11:35.110
I took his, took his advice.

00:11:35.110 --> 00:11:37.610
So what is it that we
learned about these couples?

00:11:37.610 --> 00:11:39.380
Well, Dr. Gottman
was able to notice

00:11:39.380 --> 00:11:42.130
that the couples who'd
ended up divorcing, there

00:11:42.130 --> 00:11:45.880
were four patterns that were
specifically and incredibly

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:48.280
destructive to relationships.

00:11:48.280 --> 00:11:49.890
So if you'll take
a look up here,

00:11:49.890 --> 00:11:52.840
you notice that criticism
is the first one.

00:11:52.840 --> 00:11:55.780
Criticism is incredibly
common in relationships.

00:11:55.780 --> 00:11:56.780
It's incredibly common.

00:11:56.780 --> 00:11:58.690
I'm sure you're probably
thinking, oh yeah,

00:11:58.690 --> 00:12:01.130
I know what
criticism feels like.

00:12:01.130 --> 00:12:03.390
I definitely have somebody
that criticizes me.

00:12:03.390 --> 00:12:07.590
It's my mom, it's my wife,
I criticize my partner,

00:12:07.590 --> 00:12:09.030
whatever it might be.

00:12:09.030 --> 00:12:13.490
But criticism comes up in
relationships all the time.

00:12:13.490 --> 00:12:17.080
It looks like when you have
a complaint about something,

00:12:17.080 --> 00:12:20.080
whatever it might be, the thing
that I complain most about

00:12:20.080 --> 00:12:22.770
are the clothes that are
left next to the bed.

00:12:22.770 --> 00:12:26.760
So my husband has this habit
of undressing before bed,

00:12:26.760 --> 00:12:27.960
and then there's this pile.

00:12:27.960 --> 00:12:30.960
And at the end of the week,
the pile is as tall as the bed.

00:12:30.960 --> 00:12:32.750
Do you know what
I'm talking about?

00:12:32.750 --> 00:12:35.785
So I could either
criticize my partner

00:12:35.785 --> 00:12:37.910
and I could say something
like, you're such a slob,

00:12:37.910 --> 00:12:39.950
you treat this home
like a frat house.

00:12:39.950 --> 00:12:42.610
Or I could be gentle.

00:12:42.610 --> 00:12:44.310
So the antidotes
are in the blue.

00:12:44.310 --> 00:12:47.700
And I could complain
rather than criticize.

00:12:47.700 --> 00:12:53.500
Criticism looks like a
globalizing criticism

00:12:53.500 --> 00:12:55.480
of your partner's deficiencies.

00:12:55.480 --> 00:12:58.200
So you may say to your
partner, you're a slob.

00:12:58.200 --> 00:12:59.250
That's criticism.

00:12:59.250 --> 00:13:02.230
But if you really want to do
what the masters are doing,

00:13:02.230 --> 00:13:04.370
you would complain
without blaming.

00:13:04.370 --> 00:13:08.070
You would say, you know, I'm not
so hot on all of these clothes

00:13:08.070 --> 00:13:09.141
next to the bed.

00:13:09.141 --> 00:13:11.640
I would really appreciate it
if you were to take the clothes

00:13:11.640 --> 00:13:12.930
and put them in the hamper.

00:13:12.930 --> 00:13:15.145
So that's what the
masters are doing.

00:13:15.145 --> 00:13:17.520
I'm not telling you not to
complain in your relationship,

00:13:17.520 --> 00:13:20.240
I'm just asking that
you don't criticize.

00:13:20.240 --> 00:13:21.750
OK?

00:13:21.750 --> 00:13:23.450
Second one is defensiveness.

00:13:23.450 --> 00:13:25.950
So criticism and
defensiveness go hand in hand.

00:13:25.950 --> 00:13:28.970
Defensiveness is warding
off a perceived attack.

00:13:28.970 --> 00:13:31.670
So if your partner is
a master criticizer,

00:13:31.670 --> 00:13:34.080
you are going to become
a master defender.

00:13:34.080 --> 00:13:38.440
And criticism can look
like, well, I don't do that,

00:13:38.440 --> 00:13:40.490
but did you see this over here?

00:13:40.490 --> 00:13:42.620
And you're sort of,
like, counterattacking.

00:13:42.620 --> 00:13:46.400
Defensiveness can also
look like whining.

00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:49.550
Oh, why do you
always pick on me?

00:13:49.550 --> 00:13:53.290
So the masters, instead
of defending themselves,

00:13:53.290 --> 00:13:56.160
they're noticing what it is that
their partner is criticizing

00:13:56.160 --> 00:13:57.400
or complaining about.

00:13:57.400 --> 00:14:00.360
And instead, they're taking
a small piece of that

00:14:00.360 --> 00:14:01.980
and taking responsibility.

00:14:01.980 --> 00:14:04.500
So my husband, if I'm going
to criticize him and say,

00:14:04.500 --> 00:14:07.030
you're such a
slob, he might say,

00:14:07.030 --> 00:14:09.960
yeah, you know what, those
clothes have been there

00:14:09.960 --> 00:14:11.920
for a week and I
haven't picked them up.

00:14:11.920 --> 00:14:14.740
He's taking some small
responsibility of it.

00:14:14.740 --> 00:14:17.460
You do not have
to take the blame.

00:14:17.460 --> 00:14:19.350
But if you can find
a piece of that

00:14:19.350 --> 00:14:24.140
to take responsibility for, it
easily diffuses the situation.

00:14:24.140 --> 00:14:24.880
Contempt.

00:14:24.880 --> 00:14:29.340
Contempt is what Dr. Gottman
refers to as sulfuric acid

00:14:29.340 --> 00:14:30.260
on the relationship.

00:14:30.260 --> 00:14:33.990
It is the most potent of
all four of the Horsemen.

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:37.090
Contempt is something that comes
later on in the relationship.

00:14:37.090 --> 00:14:40.992
We see it happening much
later as well as stonewalling.

00:14:40.992 --> 00:14:44.460
But contempt is when you
believe, you truly believe,

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:46.530
that you are better
than your partner.

00:14:46.530 --> 00:14:47.990
It looks like this.

00:14:47.990 --> 00:14:51.300
I'm smarter, I'm
cleaner, I'm wiser,

00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:54.190
I'm better looking
than my partner.

00:14:54.190 --> 00:14:57.725
And it comes across
in statements that

00:14:57.725 --> 00:14:59.600
are really, really hurtful.

00:14:59.600 --> 00:15:02.080
In fact, Dr. Gottman
found that if I'm

00:15:02.080 --> 00:15:05.950
contemptuous to my partner,
in the next four years,

00:15:05.950 --> 00:15:09.190
he is more likely to have
communicable diseases.

00:15:09.190 --> 00:15:11.640
It takes an effect on
your immune system.

00:15:11.640 --> 00:15:16.361
It actually starts to work and
chip away at the immune system.

00:15:16.361 --> 00:15:17.860
So if you want to
hurt your partner,

00:15:17.860 --> 00:15:19.490
if you want them to
be out sick a lot,

00:15:19.490 --> 00:15:21.980
then just be contemptuous.

00:15:21.980 --> 00:15:25.100
What are the masters doing
rather than being contemptuous?

00:15:25.100 --> 00:15:27.630
The masters are scanning
their environment

00:15:27.630 --> 00:15:30.880
for what it is that their
partner is doing right.

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:32.530
If you find that
you are starting

00:15:32.530 --> 00:15:35.530
to slip into contempt, if you
find that you are starting

00:15:35.530 --> 00:15:37.740
to think of your partner
in contemptuous ways,

00:15:37.740 --> 00:15:40.210
you can change your
brain by starting

00:15:40.210 --> 00:15:44.060
to recognize what is it that
I truly love and appreciate

00:15:44.060 --> 00:15:44.930
about my partner.

00:15:44.930 --> 00:15:47.900
My partner may not
be the smartest,

00:15:47.900 --> 00:15:50.770
but my partner is an
incredibly hard worker.

00:15:50.770 --> 00:15:53.990
My partner may not
be the sexiest,

00:15:53.990 --> 00:15:56.850
but my partner is an
incredible father.

00:15:56.850 --> 00:15:59.080
So you can start
to train your brain

00:15:59.080 --> 00:16:01.400
to be looking at your
partner in fond ways

00:16:01.400 --> 00:16:03.000
and thinking of
what are the things

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:04.980
that I really
appreciate about them.

00:16:04.980 --> 00:16:06.500
Stonewalling.

00:16:06.500 --> 00:16:07.730
This is an interesting one.

00:16:07.730 --> 00:16:11.110
So Dr. Gottman found that
something was happening.

00:16:11.110 --> 00:16:13.090
So let's go back
to the Love Lab.

00:16:13.090 --> 00:16:15.020
He's looking at
husband and wife.

00:16:15.020 --> 00:16:17.510
And he notices husband
is starting to escalate,

00:16:17.510 --> 00:16:19.360
he's heart rate's
starting to go up.

00:16:19.360 --> 00:16:21.740
And then all of a
sudden, he disengages

00:16:21.740 --> 00:16:22.730
from the conversation.

00:16:22.730 --> 00:16:26.150
His eyes are cast to the floor,
and he's no longer paying

00:16:26.150 --> 00:16:28.500
attention to his partner.

00:16:28.500 --> 00:16:30.470
Then he went back and
he asked these guys,

00:16:30.470 --> 00:16:32.250
he said, hey, what's going on.

00:16:32.250 --> 00:16:33.440
What are you doing?

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:36.270
I noticed that in this
part of the conversation,

00:16:36.270 --> 00:16:38.170
your heart rate
started to go up.

00:16:38.170 --> 00:16:39.660
What was going on?

00:16:39.660 --> 00:16:42.060
He found that
people were starting

00:16:42.060 --> 00:16:43.810
to psychologically soothe.

00:16:43.810 --> 00:16:45.460
And in order to
psychologically soothe

00:16:45.460 --> 00:16:47.085
when they were starting
to feel flooded

00:16:47.085 --> 00:16:49.130
in these contemptuous
conversations, these really

00:16:49.130 --> 00:16:52.380
tough conversations, they
would completely disengage.

00:16:52.380 --> 00:16:54.070
They're physically
still present,

00:16:54.070 --> 00:16:56.500
but they're
emotionally disengaged

00:16:56.500 --> 00:16:58.930
and they are
cognitively disengaging

00:16:58.930 --> 00:17:00.630
from the conversation.

00:17:00.630 --> 00:17:02.690
80% of the time it's
happening with men.

00:17:02.690 --> 00:17:04.800
Doesn't mean that
women don't stonewall,

00:17:04.800 --> 00:17:08.030
it just simply means that
it's more common for men.

00:17:08.030 --> 00:17:09.720
So what is it that
the masters are

00:17:09.720 --> 00:17:13.170
doing instead of disengaging
from that conversation?

00:17:13.170 --> 00:17:15.240
They're doing psychological
self-soothing.

00:17:15.240 --> 00:17:17.619
This would mean that
they might indicate, hey,

00:17:17.619 --> 00:17:21.890
you know what, I can't have
this conversation right now.

00:17:21.890 --> 00:17:23.190
I need to take a break.

00:17:23.190 --> 00:17:24.839
Or they start to breathe.

00:17:24.839 --> 00:17:26.810
Whatever it might be,
they're taking a break

00:17:26.810 --> 00:17:28.349
and they're not
allowing themselves

00:17:28.349 --> 00:17:30.160
to disengage from
the conversation

00:17:30.160 --> 00:17:33.780
because that will only
escalate the partner further.

00:17:33.780 --> 00:17:34.400
OK.

00:17:34.400 --> 00:17:36.740
Before I go on, I
just want to ask,

00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:39.132
does anybody have questions
about the Four Horsemen?

00:17:39.132 --> 00:17:41.090
These are the four
behaviors that have come up.

00:17:41.090 --> 00:17:42.007
Yes?

00:17:42.007 --> 00:17:44.340
AUDIENCE: I'm confused in
that you describe stonewalling

00:17:44.340 --> 00:17:48.465
as disengaging as
psychological self-soothing,

00:17:48.465 --> 00:17:51.315
but then what you should
do is also disengage

00:17:51.315 --> 00:17:52.720
in psychological self-soothing?

00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:53.470
LAURA HECK: Right.

00:17:53.470 --> 00:17:54.540
Exactly.

00:17:54.540 --> 00:17:56.640
So, mic?

00:17:56.640 --> 00:17:58.120
Oh, repeat the question, OK.

00:17:58.120 --> 00:18:01.890
So she's confused about the
psychological self-soothing.

00:18:01.890 --> 00:18:04.320
So what's happening
is that there's

00:18:04.320 --> 00:18:06.660
this feeling of feeling
emotionally flooded

00:18:06.660 --> 00:18:09.070
that comes up when
you are in an argument

00:18:09.070 --> 00:18:12.190
or you're having a
conflict conversation.

00:18:12.190 --> 00:18:14.846
And so as you start to
feel emotionally flooded,

00:18:14.846 --> 00:18:16.720
we know that that's
happening physiologically

00:18:16.720 --> 00:18:18.680
because the heart is
starting to beat faster.

00:18:18.680 --> 00:18:22.300
When it reaches up and
over 100 beats per minute,

00:18:22.300 --> 00:18:25.295
and for people who are
incredibly fit, like Alison,

00:18:25.295 --> 00:18:27.940
it may be more like 95, right?

00:18:27.940 --> 00:18:32.000
So once it reaches up and
over 100 beats per minute,

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:33.880
your body is starting
to release chemicals

00:18:33.880 --> 00:18:35.570
that tell you fight or flight.

00:18:35.570 --> 00:18:39.900
And in order to do that, people
shut down and they curl down

00:18:39.900 --> 00:18:42.940
and they become disengaged
from the conversation.

00:18:42.940 --> 00:18:45.080
What the masters
are doing instead,

00:18:45.080 --> 00:18:47.050
when they start to feel
the flooding come up,

00:18:47.050 --> 00:18:48.591
is they're taking
a break and they're

00:18:48.591 --> 00:18:49.910
stopping that conversation.

00:18:49.910 --> 00:18:54.490
Because what stonewalling
looks like is this.

00:18:54.490 --> 00:18:56.360
And what a partner
sees is you don't

00:18:56.360 --> 00:18:59.210
care enough to have a
conversation with me right now.

00:18:59.210 --> 00:19:00.280
They escalate.

00:19:00.280 --> 00:19:02.840
So the conversation continues
to go round and round.

00:19:02.840 --> 00:19:05.939
The more I raise my voice,
the more you shut down.

00:19:05.939 --> 00:19:07.480
If you're not paying
attention to me,

00:19:07.480 --> 00:19:11.440
now I'm going to really start
to throw some fireballs at you.

00:19:11.440 --> 00:19:12.930
Verbal fireballs.

00:19:12.930 --> 00:19:15.911
Any other questions?

00:19:15.911 --> 00:19:16.410
Yeah.

00:19:16.410 --> 00:19:19.344
AUDIENCE: The reflex
is physiological.

00:19:19.344 --> 00:19:21.010
LAURA HECK: Physiological
self-soothing,

00:19:21.010 --> 00:19:23.670
to start to take a break.

00:19:23.670 --> 00:19:26.220
So what we teach couples is if
you feel like you're starting

00:19:26.220 --> 00:19:28.510
to feel flooded,
emotionally flooded,

00:19:28.510 --> 00:19:30.750
then let's take a
20 minute break.

00:19:30.750 --> 00:19:33.180
We'll take about 20 minutes
for women, about 25 minutes

00:19:33.180 --> 00:19:34.080
for men.

00:19:34.080 --> 00:19:35.520
Go for a walk.

00:19:35.520 --> 00:19:37.910
Maybe clean.

00:19:37.910 --> 00:19:39.270
That would be what I would do.

00:19:39.270 --> 00:19:42.320
Take a bath, pet the dog,
whatever it might be.

00:19:42.320 --> 00:19:44.530
And then you start to decrease.

00:19:44.530 --> 00:19:46.095
OK.

00:19:46.095 --> 00:19:48.420
So now I want to start
talking about, we've

00:19:48.420 --> 00:19:50.650
talked about the four
destructive patterns

00:19:50.650 --> 00:19:52.000
that Dr. Gottman discovered.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:55.350
What is it that the disasters
of relationships are doing?

00:19:55.350 --> 00:19:59.270
What will cause, if
left unattended to,

00:19:59.270 --> 00:20:00.330
what will cause divorce?

00:20:00.330 --> 00:20:02.090
What will cause
relationship demise?

00:20:02.090 --> 00:20:04.150
I do want to say
that you probably,

00:20:04.150 --> 00:20:07.130
if you were like a med student
and you're going through all

00:20:07.130 --> 00:20:09.630
of the diseases and you're
starting to recognize symptoms

00:20:09.630 --> 00:20:11.390
of these diseases
in yourself, it's

00:20:11.390 --> 00:20:13.220
a lot like the Four Horsemen.

00:20:13.220 --> 00:20:15.560
You can still have a
healthy relationship

00:20:15.560 --> 00:20:17.610
with the Four Horsemen.

00:20:17.610 --> 00:20:21.890
But you also have to look at
some of the ways in which you

00:20:21.890 --> 00:20:23.870
can change and transform those.

00:20:23.870 --> 00:20:27.440
So if those are what are the
difficulties that couples

00:20:27.440 --> 00:20:29.910
are having, what are the
things that Dr. Gottman found

00:20:29.910 --> 00:20:32.210
will increase and make
your relationship better?

00:20:32.210 --> 00:20:33.880
So we'll go through
the principles.

00:20:33.880 --> 00:20:36.990
So principle number one
has to do with having

00:20:36.990 --> 00:20:39.830
a strong marital foundation.

00:20:39.830 --> 00:20:41.460
It's called the friendship.

00:20:41.460 --> 00:20:43.370
I know it sounds kind
of funny that if you're

00:20:43.370 --> 00:20:44.745
married to this
person, of course

00:20:44.745 --> 00:20:45.990
you're going to be friends.

00:20:45.990 --> 00:20:48.640
But imagine being with
somebody for 40 years.

00:20:48.640 --> 00:20:51.690
I know with my own personal
life, sometimes I would ask,

00:20:51.690 --> 00:20:53.740
are my grandparents
even friends.

00:20:53.740 --> 00:20:56.280
Doesn't even seem like they
like each other anymore.

00:20:56.280 --> 00:20:57.820
So Dr. Gottman
found that in order

00:20:57.820 --> 00:20:59.480
to have a strong
relationship, it

00:20:59.480 --> 00:21:02.520
has to be a foundation
of friendship.

00:21:02.520 --> 00:21:05.150
In order to increase
your friendship,

00:21:05.150 --> 00:21:08.880
you have to know your partner's
inner world in and out.

00:21:08.880 --> 00:21:11.370
You have to know
everything about them.

00:21:11.370 --> 00:21:13.260
When you start a
relationship, when

00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:14.980
you start to fall in
love with someone,

00:21:14.980 --> 00:21:17.410
you're trying to decide,
is this my forever.

00:21:17.410 --> 00:21:19.880
So you might ask questions
like, well, what is

00:21:19.880 --> 00:21:21.640
your grandmother's maiden name?

00:21:21.640 --> 00:21:24.179
And what kind of is
your favorite animal?

00:21:24.179 --> 00:21:26.720
What's your favorite color, and
what's your favorite holiday?

00:21:26.720 --> 00:21:28.230
What do you want to
be when you grow up?

00:21:28.230 --> 00:21:30.360
You ask all of these
questions to get to know them.

00:21:30.360 --> 00:21:32.800
And soon enough
you decide, OK, I'm

00:21:32.800 --> 00:21:34.130
going to settle in with you.

00:21:34.130 --> 00:21:35.650
You are my forever.

00:21:35.650 --> 00:21:37.580
But then 25 years goes by.

00:21:37.580 --> 00:21:41.680
This person has changed, but you
haven't asked those questions.

00:21:41.680 --> 00:21:44.870
You have no idea who this
person is any longer.

00:21:44.870 --> 00:21:48.170
Love Maps is this
metaphorical idea

00:21:48.170 --> 00:21:52.180
that you have a map of your
partner's internal world.

00:21:52.180 --> 00:21:55.710
The goal is to make this map
as detailed and up to date

00:21:55.710 --> 00:21:56.820
as possible.

00:21:56.820 --> 00:21:58.090
How do you do that?

00:21:58.090 --> 00:21:59.790
So I'm going to be giving tips.

00:21:59.790 --> 00:22:02.520
You can start to use this
every day in your life.

00:22:02.520 --> 00:22:04.556
You ask your partner
open-ended questions.

00:22:04.556 --> 00:22:05.930
These are not
questions that they

00:22:05.930 --> 00:22:09.010
can answer with a simple yes
or no or one word answer.

00:22:09.010 --> 00:22:10.840
You're asking your
partner questions

00:22:10.840 --> 00:22:15.170
that really starts to chip
away at who this person is.

00:22:15.170 --> 00:22:18.684
Maybe you ask them about
their hopes and dreams.

00:22:18.684 --> 00:22:20.600
What do you want to do
in the next five years?

00:22:20.600 --> 00:22:23.370
What is one thing that you
have, a goal that you have yet

00:22:23.370 --> 00:22:24.190
to realize?

00:22:24.190 --> 00:22:28.890
Or how do you feel about this
Republican Party right now?

00:22:28.890 --> 00:22:31.450
I mean, what do you think?

00:22:31.450 --> 00:22:35.140
Or it might be a question
like, you really,

00:22:35.140 --> 00:22:37.780
really wanted to be a mother,
and we haven't had children.

00:22:37.780 --> 00:22:40.780
How do you feel about not
having children right now?

00:22:40.780 --> 00:22:43.310
These are open-ended questions.

00:22:43.310 --> 00:22:47.110
So for those of you
who have an iPhone,

00:22:47.110 --> 00:22:49.940
you can actually
download an app.

00:22:49.940 --> 00:22:52.030
It's $1.99 and if you
shake it, it gives you

00:22:52.030 --> 00:22:53.470
a new open-ended question.

00:22:53.470 --> 00:22:57.290
So no matter where you
are, you will always

00:22:57.290 --> 00:22:59.330
have an open-ended question.

00:22:59.330 --> 00:23:02.806
You don't have to come
up with them yourself.

00:23:02.806 --> 00:23:06.310
OK, so we're still talking about
that foundation of friendship.

00:23:06.310 --> 00:23:09.920
Number two is nurturing the
fondness and admiration.

00:23:09.920 --> 00:23:13.830
Simply put, is that you are
choosing on a daily basis

00:23:13.830 --> 00:23:17.290
to scan your environment for the
positives of what your partner

00:23:17.290 --> 00:23:19.090
is doing versus the negatives.

00:23:19.090 --> 00:23:19.590
OK?

00:23:19.590 --> 00:23:21.780
So we're going back to the bed.

00:23:21.780 --> 00:23:25.550
I wake up in the morning,
I look over at my husband,

00:23:25.550 --> 00:23:28.200
he has drool coming
out of his mouth.

00:23:28.200 --> 00:23:30.666
He has, like, retainer
in so that he's not

00:23:30.666 --> 00:23:32.290
chewing on his tongue
or doing whatever

00:23:32.290 --> 00:23:35.946
people do with retainers in.

00:23:35.946 --> 00:23:38.840
I look, I see, I notice that
the clothes are on the floor.

00:23:38.840 --> 00:23:40.270
I have to step over the clothes.

00:23:40.270 --> 00:23:42.550
So instantly I'm starting
to think and create

00:23:42.550 --> 00:23:44.230
this world in which
my husband has

00:23:44.230 --> 00:23:46.810
done all of these wrong things.

00:23:46.810 --> 00:23:50.290
Or I can wake up in the
morning and I can look over

00:23:50.290 --> 00:23:56.220
at my husband and I think, well,
he sure looks sexy over there.

00:23:56.220 --> 00:23:59.360
He's been working out, I
see some biceps coming in.

00:23:59.360 --> 00:24:01.932
And maybe I look
a little bit more

00:24:01.932 --> 00:24:04.140
and I notice that he's curled
around our one-year-old

00:24:04.140 --> 00:24:06.340
that he pulled into bed in
the middle of the night,

00:24:06.340 --> 00:24:08.230
and I didn't even notice.

00:24:08.230 --> 00:24:10.430
Like wow, what a great dad.

00:24:10.430 --> 00:24:13.920
Thank you, I enjoyed eight
hours of uninterrupted sleep.

00:24:13.920 --> 00:24:15.450
So I step over that
pile of clothes.

00:24:15.450 --> 00:24:16.990
I don't even notice
them this time

00:24:16.990 --> 00:24:20.050
because I'm scanning my
environment for the positives.

00:24:20.050 --> 00:24:21.780
What is it that my
husband is doing right

00:24:21.780 --> 00:24:24.090
versus what he's doing wrong?

00:24:24.090 --> 00:24:26.960
You can use this with
your children as well.

00:24:26.960 --> 00:24:29.630
If you are waiting
to correct your child

00:24:29.630 --> 00:24:32.560
for every wrong
thing that they do,

00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:36.280
do you really think that they're
going to be looking for you

00:24:36.280 --> 00:24:39.490
when they achieve something
wonderful and great?

00:24:39.490 --> 00:24:42.200
Or are you going to wait
to applaud your child when

00:24:42.200 --> 00:24:44.130
they're doing something
right and really

00:24:44.130 --> 00:24:46.020
make that a big point?

00:24:46.020 --> 00:24:46.850
That is awesome.

00:24:46.850 --> 00:24:50.850
Thank you so much for putting
that back, that is fantastic.

00:24:50.850 --> 00:24:52.647
Also, with your
relationships with,

00:24:52.647 --> 00:24:54.230
maybe the people
that you're managing.

00:24:54.230 --> 00:24:57.240
If you are rewarding people
and scanning for the things

00:24:57.240 --> 00:24:58.710
that they're doing
right, they're

00:24:58.710 --> 00:25:02.590
more able to do those
things correctly.

00:25:02.590 --> 00:25:04.470
So fondness and
admiration is really

00:25:04.470 --> 00:25:07.460
about thinking about your
partner on a daily basis,

00:25:07.460 --> 00:25:09.870
about the things that
they are doing correctly

00:25:09.870 --> 00:25:11.770
and that you really
love about them.

00:25:11.770 --> 00:25:14.140
It's about training your brain.

00:25:14.140 --> 00:25:16.160
One thing that you
can do is make it

00:25:16.160 --> 00:25:17.990
a habit every single day.

00:25:17.990 --> 00:25:20.160
And if you can't
remember, do this.

00:25:20.160 --> 00:25:23.970
Set an alarm on your phone to
send a text to your partner.

00:25:23.970 --> 00:25:29.200
And I want you every single day
to say thank you so much for,

00:25:29.200 --> 00:25:33.930
I really appreciated it when
you did this, you're so sexy,

00:25:33.930 --> 00:25:35.780
I saw you walk
out the door today

00:25:35.780 --> 00:25:38.910
and that skirt looked amazing
on you, whatever it might be.

00:25:38.910 --> 00:25:41.106
But even though
you have an alarm

00:25:41.106 --> 00:25:42.480
on your phone and
your partner is

00:25:42.480 --> 00:25:44.438
like, why does this always
come in at 2 o'clock

00:25:44.438 --> 00:25:45.560
in the afternoon.

00:25:45.560 --> 00:25:48.380
It doesn't matter
because they're

00:25:48.380 --> 00:25:51.030
going to appreciate that
you're sending it at all.

00:25:51.030 --> 00:25:55.600
So if you're going to
do that, do that now.

00:25:55.600 --> 00:25:57.960
Little pro tip.

00:25:57.960 --> 00:25:59.940
So we're still talking
about friendship

00:25:59.940 --> 00:26:02.560
and nurturing this
friendship foundation.

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:05.170
The third principle
is turning toward.

00:26:05.170 --> 00:26:07.800
The motto is small things often.

00:26:07.800 --> 00:26:09.710
With everything that
Dr. Gottman does,

00:26:09.710 --> 00:26:11.750
it is a motto of
small things often.

00:26:11.750 --> 00:26:15.762
You can change the trajectory
of your relationship

00:26:15.762 --> 00:26:19.620
simply by doing small things
every day consistently.

00:26:19.620 --> 00:26:22.830
You do not, I will tell you
this, Valentine's Day gentleman

00:26:22.830 --> 00:26:24.970
and ladies, you
do not have to buy

00:26:24.970 --> 00:26:29.280
that $5,000 ring
or that $50,000 car

00:26:29.280 --> 00:26:32.340
or take them on that
$10,000 vacation.

00:26:32.340 --> 00:26:34.064
That means nothing.

00:26:34.064 --> 00:26:36.480
But if you're sending those
appreciations every single day

00:26:36.480 --> 00:26:39.300
at 2 o'clock for 365 days?

00:26:39.300 --> 00:26:40.530
Boom.

00:26:40.530 --> 00:26:43.030
Free.

00:26:43.030 --> 00:26:46.550
So we're looking for ways
to turn toward our partner.

00:26:46.550 --> 00:26:47.740
So here's the deal.

00:26:47.740 --> 00:26:51.360
Our partners, on a daily
basis, are turning towards us.

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:53.879
And the key is being able
to recognize when they're

00:26:53.879 --> 00:26:55.920
turning toward because
what turning toward really

00:26:55.920 --> 00:26:58.890
is, is it's a small, subtle
way of saying I have a want,

00:26:58.890 --> 00:27:02.070
a need, a desire,
are you there for me.

00:27:02.070 --> 00:27:04.320
So here's what turning
toward looks like.

00:27:04.320 --> 00:27:07.370
Maybe I'm standing at
the sink doing dishes

00:27:07.370 --> 00:27:10.520
and I notice that it's
starting to snow, which it did

00:27:10.520 --> 00:27:12.110
in Salt Lake City yesterday.

00:27:12.110 --> 00:27:15.440
It's 80 degrees here, Salt
Lake City, it's snowing.

00:27:15.440 --> 00:27:19.810
And I say, are you kidding me?

00:27:19.810 --> 00:27:21.020
Is that snow?

00:27:21.020 --> 00:27:23.420
And my husband's
in the other room.

00:27:23.420 --> 00:27:25.200
How is he going to
turn towards me?

00:27:25.200 --> 00:27:27.852
He's going to go, yup.

00:27:27.852 --> 00:27:28.352
That's it.

00:27:28.352 --> 00:27:30.290
That's all you have to do.

00:27:30.290 --> 00:27:32.100
Because why am I
talking out loud?

00:27:32.100 --> 00:27:34.440
You're going to say you're
just talking to yourself.

00:27:34.440 --> 00:27:36.420
Your partner's not
talking to themselves,

00:27:36.420 --> 00:27:38.070
they're talking to you.

00:27:38.070 --> 00:27:39.710
They want you to respond.

00:27:39.710 --> 00:27:42.210
And you don't have to
make it a grand response.

00:27:42.210 --> 00:27:44.720
All you have to do is go uh-huh.

00:27:44.720 --> 00:27:46.970
Just recognizing that
they're speaking to you.

00:27:46.970 --> 00:27:49.370
Bids can be overt and
they can be covert,

00:27:49.370 --> 00:27:51.520
so that would be a bit
of a covert bid, right?

00:27:51.520 --> 00:27:54.450
Overt bid would be that you
sit next to your partner

00:27:54.450 --> 00:27:56.676
on the couch and
you pull him over

00:27:56.676 --> 00:27:58.300
and you put your arm
around him and you

00:27:58.300 --> 00:28:02.900
go-- that right there is a bid.

00:28:02.900 --> 00:28:04.359
Now how does the person respond?

00:28:04.359 --> 00:28:06.150
You have three choices
to respond to a bid.

00:28:06.150 --> 00:28:09.690
You can turn toward them, which
would be like saying uh-huh.

00:28:09.690 --> 00:28:11.130
Or you go, oh yeah?

00:28:11.130 --> 00:28:12.670
Let's go upstairs.

00:28:12.670 --> 00:28:15.690
Or you can turn away
from your partner,

00:28:15.690 --> 00:28:19.310
which would mean missing their
bid or ignoring their bid.

00:28:19.310 --> 00:28:20.957
How do we ignore bids?

00:28:20.957 --> 00:28:21.540
I'll tell you.

00:28:21.540 --> 00:28:22.840
Digital distraction.

00:28:22.840 --> 00:28:24.480
That's the number
one way right now

00:28:24.480 --> 00:28:25.970
that people are ignoring bids.

00:28:25.970 --> 00:28:28.840
Whether you recognize it
or not, if you are face

00:28:28.840 --> 00:28:32.280
down on a computer or
a game, or your phone,

00:28:32.280 --> 00:28:35.324
you're going to miss
bids from your partner.

00:28:35.324 --> 00:28:38.930
So you can also turn
against your partner.

00:28:38.930 --> 00:28:41.090
If my husband's
rushing out the door

00:28:41.090 --> 00:28:45.390
and as he's rushing out the
door I say, oh, before you go,

00:28:45.390 --> 00:28:46.910
I'm going to go
grocery shopping,

00:28:46.910 --> 00:28:49.500
is there anything special that
you'd like for dinner tonight?

00:28:49.500 --> 00:28:52.110
That's really sweet
of me to ask, right?

00:28:52.110 --> 00:28:53.360
He's going to turn against me.

00:28:53.360 --> 00:28:54.860
Here's what he says.

00:28:54.860 --> 00:28:57.900
You know that Monday nights I
go out with the guys after work.

00:28:57.900 --> 00:29:00.280
Why do you always manipulate
me into staying in

00:29:00.280 --> 00:29:01.160
on these nights?

00:29:01.160 --> 00:29:03.320
That's turning against.

00:29:03.320 --> 00:29:03.820
OK?

00:29:03.820 --> 00:29:06.620
So you always have
three options.

00:29:06.620 --> 00:29:08.840
The nice part is that
with turning toward,

00:29:08.840 --> 00:29:11.450
all you have to do is just
recognize when your partner is

00:29:11.450 --> 00:29:13.880
making bids and
remember that you

00:29:13.880 --> 00:29:17.550
can turn toward them in very
small ways every single day.

00:29:17.550 --> 00:29:19.900
If you imagine that
your relationship is

00:29:19.900 --> 00:29:23.200
a lot like an emotional
bank account, every time you

00:29:23.200 --> 00:29:25.810
turn toward your partner,
you're putting a deposit in.

00:29:25.810 --> 00:29:27.720
This is important
because when something

00:29:27.720 --> 00:29:30.690
external to the
relationship really causes

00:29:30.690 --> 00:29:32.800
some pain, when
something happens,

00:29:32.800 --> 00:29:34.800
when you have a fight,
when the car breaks down,

00:29:34.800 --> 00:29:37.480
when one of the kids is being
obnoxious, and the two of you

00:29:37.480 --> 00:29:39.750
are super stressed
out, you have enough

00:29:39.750 --> 00:29:42.586
of those emotional deposits in
that bank account to buffer.

00:29:42.586 --> 00:29:44.210
So that when you take
a withdrawal out,

00:29:44.210 --> 00:29:45.460
you're not overdrawn.

00:29:45.460 --> 00:29:47.000
Does that makes sense?

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:47.500
OK.

00:29:47.500 --> 00:29:50.710
So here's the interesting part.

00:29:50.710 --> 00:29:54.706
Remember that newlywed study
that was in the apartment lab?

00:29:54.706 --> 00:29:58.240
And that all those newlyweds,
of those 17 newlyweds that

00:29:58.240 --> 00:30:01.020
ended up divorcing, they
went back and they said,

00:30:01.020 --> 00:30:03.470
what do we know
about turning toward.

00:30:03.470 --> 00:30:04.380
And they counted.

00:30:04.380 --> 00:30:09.749
They figured out that 86% of
the time, the couples that

00:30:09.749 --> 00:30:11.290
are still together,
they were turning

00:30:11.290 --> 00:30:12.550
toward each other's bids.

00:30:12.550 --> 00:30:14.820
But those that
divorced missed them.

00:30:14.820 --> 00:30:18.260
They were only turning
toward 33% of the time.

00:30:18.260 --> 00:30:21.220
You can see how important it
is to recognize those bids

00:30:21.220 --> 00:30:23.440
in your relationship, the
times when your partner is

00:30:23.440 --> 00:30:25.040
trying to reach out to you.

00:30:25.040 --> 00:30:27.959
Has a want, a need, a
desire, and how important

00:30:27.959 --> 00:30:29.750
it is that you're
recognizing it and you're

00:30:29.750 --> 00:30:33.546
choosing to turn toward rather
than away or against them.

00:30:33.546 --> 00:30:34.920
So before I move
on, does anybody

00:30:34.920 --> 00:30:38.190
have questions about maybe
the first three principles?

00:30:38.190 --> 00:30:39.730
So we have the
Love Map principle,

00:30:39.730 --> 00:30:44.830
we have fondness and admiration,
and we have the turning toward.

00:30:44.830 --> 00:30:46.320
Yeah.

00:30:46.320 --> 00:30:48.940
AUDIENCE: So I didn't
get the two positives.

00:30:48.940 --> 00:30:50.440
So if somebody
makes a bid, you can

00:30:50.440 --> 00:30:52.850
decline no, you can say yes,
and what's the third one?

00:30:52.850 --> 00:30:54.550
I didn't get the
difference here.

00:30:54.550 --> 00:30:56.670
LAURA HECK: So the
difference is that you

00:30:56.670 --> 00:30:59.780
can turn toward your
partner, which is basically

00:30:59.780 --> 00:31:03.340
any response that's positive
toward your partner's bid.

00:31:03.340 --> 00:31:05.210
You can turn away
from them, which looks

00:31:05.210 --> 00:31:06.830
a lot like ignoring a bid.

00:31:06.830 --> 00:31:08.953
And you can turn against
him, which would mean

00:31:08.953 --> 00:31:11.931
kind of lashing back at them.

00:31:11.931 --> 00:31:14.350
Any other questions?

00:31:14.350 --> 00:31:15.622
Yeah.

00:31:15.622 --> 00:31:18.550
AUDIENCE: So in your
example of your husband

00:31:18.550 --> 00:31:20.200
kind of going
against, what would

00:31:20.200 --> 00:31:23.092
be a better response
for him knowing that,

00:31:23.092 --> 00:31:25.550
if he still wants to hang out
with his buddies or whatever.

00:31:25.550 --> 00:31:26.930
LAURA HECK: That's
a great question.

00:31:26.930 --> 00:31:28.320
So what would be
a better response?

00:31:28.320 --> 00:31:29.920
If my husband was
rushing out the door

00:31:29.920 --> 00:31:32.350
and I said, honey, what would
you like for dinner tonight,

00:31:32.350 --> 00:31:33.910
I'm going to go to the store.

00:31:33.910 --> 00:31:37.480
And rather than being
rude and lashing back,

00:31:37.480 --> 00:31:40.550
he could turn around and
he could say, oh, well,

00:31:40.550 --> 00:31:43.185
that is so nice of you to offer,
but actually Monday nights

00:31:43.185 --> 00:31:45.060
is the night that I'm
going out with the guys

00:31:45.060 --> 00:31:46.560
so I won't be home tonight.

00:31:46.560 --> 00:31:49.760
So it doesn't mean that he has
to change or say yes, dear,

00:31:49.760 --> 00:31:53.220
or do what I want, but
responding back to me

00:31:53.220 --> 00:31:57.340
with, if I could sum it
up, respect and honor.

00:31:57.340 --> 00:31:59.510
By responding back
with respect and honor,

00:31:59.510 --> 00:32:02.690
then he could still
turn toward me.

00:32:02.690 --> 00:32:03.650
OK.

00:32:03.650 --> 00:32:05.920
I'm going to move on
to the next question.

00:32:05.920 --> 00:32:08.984
Anybody else have a question?

00:32:08.984 --> 00:32:09.860
All right.

00:32:09.860 --> 00:32:12.120
So principle number four.

00:32:12.120 --> 00:32:16.606
This is moving away from
the friendship foundation.

00:32:16.606 --> 00:32:18.230
We've covered the
friendship foundation

00:32:18.230 --> 00:32:21.280
and now we're starting to get
into what Dr. Gottman noticed

00:32:21.280 --> 00:32:24.970
with couples, which is letting
your partner influence you.

00:32:24.970 --> 00:32:29.040
He noticed that there was
a vast majority of couples

00:32:29.040 --> 00:32:31.600
where most of the time
they allow their partner

00:32:31.600 --> 00:32:33.170
to influence them.

00:32:33.170 --> 00:32:36.920
I have taken this to heart.

00:32:36.920 --> 00:32:39.870
When it came time to buy
a vehicle, how many of you

00:32:39.870 --> 00:32:42.530
have had like a struggle buying
vehicles in your relationship?

00:32:42.530 --> 00:32:45.740
Because one of you wants,
like, the smart car or whatever

00:32:45.740 --> 00:32:47.890
it might be, and you
want like the big Yukon,

00:32:47.890 --> 00:32:51.130
and you have to find something
in between that fits both.

00:32:51.130 --> 00:32:54.470
So this has been an exercise in
my own relationship of letting

00:32:54.470 --> 00:32:56.020
my partner influence me.

00:32:56.020 --> 00:32:59.870
And really what it comes down
to is when your partner says,

00:32:59.870 --> 00:33:04.100
I want this, your first
response is OK, yes,

00:33:04.100 --> 00:33:05.360
let's make this happen.

00:33:05.360 --> 00:33:06.860
If your partner
says, I have a dream

00:33:06.860 --> 00:33:10.590
to go back to school, that
your first thought is whatever

00:33:10.590 --> 00:33:13.910
you want, let's make it
happen, and let's find excuses

00:33:13.910 --> 00:33:15.680
why it won't work later.

00:33:15.680 --> 00:33:17.700
But oftentimes what
happens instead

00:33:17.700 --> 00:33:19.660
is that you become a roadblock.

00:33:19.660 --> 00:33:20.616
Whatever it might be.

00:33:20.616 --> 00:33:22.990
Have you ever noticed that
sometimes there's couples that

00:33:22.990 --> 00:33:25.573
there might be that one person
that it's like no matter what I

00:33:25.573 --> 00:33:30.165
want, if I want to buy
this orange juice for $3.50

00:33:30.165 --> 00:33:31.560
at the grocery store.

00:33:31.560 --> 00:33:33.870
You don't want that,
you want to buy

00:33:33.870 --> 00:33:36.362
the orange juice that's $2.99.

00:33:36.362 --> 00:33:40.430
That that extra $0.51 is going
to be an argument right now.

00:33:40.430 --> 00:33:43.600
So letting your
partner influence you,

00:33:43.600 --> 00:33:45.000
being able to negotiate.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:48.330
Being able to say, why is this
so important, tell me more.

00:33:48.330 --> 00:33:50.450
Rather than
immediately saying no.

00:33:50.450 --> 00:33:52.899
That's a big deal.

00:33:52.899 --> 00:33:54.690
So you can see there's
a statistic up here.

00:33:54.690 --> 00:34:00.550
81% divorce rate when men are
not willing to share power.

00:34:00.550 --> 00:34:02.030
Eventually what
ended up happening

00:34:02.030 --> 00:34:03.730
is that Dr. Gottman
found that when

00:34:03.730 --> 00:34:06.240
men were saying no,
when they weren't even

00:34:06.240 --> 00:34:09.050
willing to entertain
negotiation with their partner,

00:34:09.050 --> 00:34:12.949
when it was a power
struggle, 81% of those times

00:34:12.949 --> 00:34:14.840
they ended up divorcing.

00:34:14.840 --> 00:34:15.889
It's powerful.

00:34:15.889 --> 00:34:18.340
Being able to say why is
this important to you,

00:34:18.340 --> 00:34:20.250
let's just have a conversation.

00:34:20.250 --> 00:34:22.230
It's not yes, dear.

00:34:22.230 --> 00:34:23.670
I have to say that part.

00:34:23.670 --> 00:34:25.500
It's not yes, husband.

00:34:25.500 --> 00:34:27.440
It's why is this important.

00:34:27.440 --> 00:34:29.139
If it's important to
you, let's at least

00:34:29.139 --> 00:34:32.278
entertain the idea
and let's talk.

00:34:32.278 --> 00:34:33.290
Any questions?

00:34:33.290 --> 00:34:34.530
Yeah.

00:34:34.530 --> 00:34:36.780
AUDIENCE: Which year
was the study made?

00:34:36.780 --> 00:34:40.382
Because like I read pretty
much the reverse statistics.

00:34:40.382 --> 00:34:41.840
LAURA HECK: The
