00:34:59.520 --> 00:35:04.290
now that they're growing,
the male actually

00:35:04.290 --> 00:35:08.351
are insecure and searching all
their life, or the other way

00:35:08.351 --> 00:35:09.100
around, the women.

00:35:09.100 --> 00:35:12.265
And I'm not Gen X, I'm Gen
Y. I'm not grown up here,

00:35:12.265 --> 00:35:13.890
my parents aren't
divorced or anything.

00:35:13.890 --> 00:35:16.390
So I was wondering
if this is coming

00:35:16.390 --> 00:35:18.940
from the '80s, from
the '90s, et cetera.

00:35:18.940 --> 00:35:20.260
LAURA HECK: So it is.

00:35:20.260 --> 00:35:23.280
Most of Dr. Gottman's
research, especially

00:35:23.280 --> 00:35:26.710
with the research
lab, is coming from I

00:35:26.710 --> 00:35:29.430
think the '90s, actually.

00:35:29.430 --> 00:35:31.750
But I would be interested
to know what it is.

00:35:31.750 --> 00:35:34.380
Are you saying that
the inverse of it

00:35:34.380 --> 00:35:36.547
is that women are
unwilling to yield power?

00:35:36.547 --> 00:35:37.880
AUDIENCE: No, nothing like that.

00:35:37.880 --> 00:35:44.700
What I'm saying is that this
strong kind of macho culture

00:35:44.700 --> 00:35:46.717
has gone away for the years.

00:35:46.717 --> 00:35:49.050
LAURA HECK: OK, now I know
where you're going with that.

00:35:49.050 --> 00:35:50.310
Yeah.

00:35:50.310 --> 00:35:52.310
So yes, to answer your
question, the research

00:35:52.310 --> 00:35:54.000
does go back quite
a bit because he

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:56.690
did the majority of his
research over the last 40 years.

00:35:56.690 --> 00:35:59.430
So a lot of it is
not going to cite

00:35:59.430 --> 00:36:02.580
things that are happening
now and moving forward.

00:36:02.580 --> 00:36:04.030
Yeah.

00:36:04.030 --> 00:36:09.254
Any other questions about
yielding power, saying yes?

00:36:09.254 --> 00:36:11.090
OK.

00:36:11.090 --> 00:36:14.610
So of the complaints that
come in, so I had mentioned

00:36:14.610 --> 00:36:16.400
I'm a couples therapist.

00:36:16.400 --> 00:36:17.380
The number one thing.

00:36:17.380 --> 00:36:21.440
Couples come in, they say we're
having trouble communicating,

00:36:21.440 --> 00:36:23.300
we have conflict all the time.

00:36:23.300 --> 00:36:26.130
Dr. Gottman really
wanted to figure out

00:36:26.130 --> 00:36:28.870
what is it that the masters are
doing to solve their conflict.

00:36:28.870 --> 00:36:30.930
So what I will start
talking about now

00:36:30.930 --> 00:36:35.050
is what is it that they're
doing when it comes to conflict.

00:36:35.050 --> 00:36:37.900
You can have two
types of conflict.

00:36:37.900 --> 00:36:41.110
It's either solvable
or it's perpetual.

00:36:41.110 --> 00:36:44.010
Fundamental difference
between solvable problems

00:36:44.010 --> 00:36:46.690
and perpetual problems.

00:36:46.690 --> 00:36:48.160
What percentage,
I'm just curious,

00:36:48.160 --> 00:36:50.287
what percentage do you
think of happy couples

00:36:50.287 --> 00:36:52.620
do you think they would be
able to solve their problems?

00:36:52.620 --> 00:36:55.920
Happy, masters of relationships.

00:36:55.920 --> 00:36:58.910
What percentage are able
to solve their problems?

00:36:58.910 --> 00:37:01.160
Or what percentage of problems
are they able to solve?

00:37:01.160 --> 00:37:03.060
That's probably a
better way to put it.

00:37:03.060 --> 00:37:05.610
What do you think?

00:37:05.610 --> 00:37:07.825
50%?

00:37:07.825 --> 00:37:08.325
80%?

00:37:10.880 --> 00:37:11.640
Anybody else?

00:37:11.640 --> 00:37:12.910
What's that?

00:37:12.910 --> 00:37:13.410
30%?

00:37:13.410 --> 00:37:14.490
That's low.

00:37:14.490 --> 00:37:16.720
Bar is low for you, huh?

00:37:16.720 --> 00:37:21.060
OK, so truth be told,
Dr. Gottman found

00:37:21.060 --> 00:37:24.350
that of all conflict with
couples that were thriving,

00:37:24.350 --> 00:37:26.770
that were happy, they
were only able to solve

00:37:26.770 --> 00:37:29.630
31% of those problems.

00:37:29.630 --> 00:37:31.980
Yeah, so is that
encouraging for you?

00:37:31.980 --> 00:37:33.984
Or is that discouraging?

00:37:33.984 --> 00:37:36.400
Like, that you're going to
have 69% of these problems that

00:37:36.400 --> 00:37:38.870
are just going to stick around
for the rest of your life.

00:37:38.870 --> 00:37:40.900
There was one researcher,
and I like this,

00:37:40.900 --> 00:37:42.790
that he said when you
stand up on that altar,

00:37:42.790 --> 00:37:45.440
really what you're doing
is you are agreeing

00:37:45.440 --> 00:37:48.140
to the 50 years of problems
that the two of you

00:37:48.140 --> 00:37:48.890
are going to have.

00:37:48.890 --> 00:37:53.490
For the next 50 years, we are
signing up for this conflict.

00:37:53.490 --> 00:37:55.460
What Dr. Gottman found
is that he was doing

00:37:55.460 --> 00:37:56.650
these longitudinal studies.

00:37:56.650 --> 00:37:58.240
He would have these
couples come in,

00:37:58.240 --> 00:38:00.600
he'd hook them up to their
little jiggle-ometers,

00:38:00.600 --> 00:38:03.520
and he would say,
nice to see you again.

00:38:03.520 --> 00:38:05.660
Your clothes have changed,
your hair has changed,

00:38:05.660 --> 00:38:07.740
it's nice to see you
after four years.

00:38:07.740 --> 00:38:09.600
I want you guys to
just choose a conflict

00:38:09.600 --> 00:38:10.850
and just kind of sort it out.

00:38:10.850 --> 00:38:13.280
Something that the two
of you can't agree on.

00:38:13.280 --> 00:38:15.340
What happened?

00:38:15.340 --> 00:38:18.360
He said that he could put the
tape of them rolling four years

00:38:18.360 --> 00:38:20.120
prior to the tape of them now.

00:38:20.120 --> 00:38:21.900
A few more gray
hairs, their clothes

00:38:21.900 --> 00:38:24.420
are a little more in style,
maybe a few more pounds.

00:38:24.420 --> 00:38:26.160
Same conflict.

00:38:26.160 --> 00:38:28.550
Boom, boom, boom, boom.

00:38:28.550 --> 00:38:29.890
Same conflict.

00:38:29.890 --> 00:38:33.010
So that means that these
couples, 69% of them,

00:38:33.010 --> 00:38:34.510
they're perpetual problems.

00:38:34.510 --> 00:38:36.210
Why are they perpetual?

00:38:36.210 --> 00:38:39.650
It's because we are unique,
wonderful human beings

00:38:39.650 --> 00:38:45.680
and what makes me up, my value
system, my likes, my dislikes,

00:38:45.680 --> 00:38:47.720
is different from my
partner's value system,

00:38:47.720 --> 00:38:48.960
likes, and dislikes.

00:38:48.960 --> 00:38:51.580
It's the fundamental things
that make me who I am.

00:38:51.580 --> 00:38:55.920
So if I'm an introvert,
which I am, believe me,

00:38:55.920 --> 00:38:59.480
and my husband is an extrovert,
when Friday night comes around,

00:38:59.480 --> 00:39:01.980
what do I want to do?

00:39:01.980 --> 00:39:04.830
I want to watch Netflix,
I want to eat ice cream,

00:39:04.830 --> 00:39:07.630
I want to sit on the couch
and I just want to veg.

00:39:07.630 --> 00:39:09.020
What does my husband want to do?

00:39:09.020 --> 00:39:11.540
He wants to go out
every Friday night.

00:39:11.540 --> 00:39:12.550
Is this a conflict?

00:39:12.550 --> 00:39:13.910
Absolutely.

00:39:13.910 --> 00:39:16.280
So other differences.

00:39:16.280 --> 00:39:17.030
Am I neat?

00:39:17.030 --> 00:39:18.080
Yes, I'm neat.

00:39:18.080 --> 00:39:20.010
Is my husband not so neat?

00:39:20.010 --> 00:39:21.040
Absolutely.

00:39:21.040 --> 00:39:23.610
These are things
about the two of us

00:39:23.610 --> 00:39:25.080
that are a little different.

00:39:25.080 --> 00:39:27.880
And so these are the
perpetual problems.

00:39:27.880 --> 00:39:29.520
The problem is
that when you don't

00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:31.980
know the difference between
perpetual and solvable,

00:39:31.980 --> 00:39:34.280
is that you end up
getting gridlocked

00:39:34.280 --> 00:39:36.680
and you think there has
to be a way to solve this.

00:39:36.680 --> 00:39:38.820
But unfortunately,
it's not about solving

00:39:38.820 --> 00:39:40.080
your perpetual problems.

00:39:40.080 --> 00:39:41.890
It's about learning
how to communicate

00:39:41.890 --> 00:39:45.020
through those perpetual problems
in a different way that's

00:39:45.020 --> 00:39:47.800
still honoring and
respecting your partner.

00:39:47.800 --> 00:39:50.470
So how are the masters
talking through

00:39:50.470 --> 00:39:55.140
those solvable problems, the
31% of those solvable problems?

00:39:55.140 --> 00:39:56.910
What are the solvable problems?

00:39:56.910 --> 00:39:59.690
These are things like, how are
we going to use our tax refund?

00:39:59.690 --> 00:40:03.031
We're obviously going
to buy a hot tub, guys.

00:40:03.031 --> 00:40:05.140
Or whose house
are we going to go

00:40:05.140 --> 00:40:08.970
to for Memorial Day, my
mom's house, your house?

00:40:08.970 --> 00:40:09.970
What are we going to do?

00:40:09.970 --> 00:40:11.219
How are we going to celebrate?

00:40:11.219 --> 00:40:12.430
These are solvable problems.

00:40:12.430 --> 00:40:17.226
They often tend to be
short-term in nature.

00:40:17.226 --> 00:40:20.370
So a solvable problem would
probably be something similar

00:40:20.370 --> 00:40:27.280
like if we can't figure out
what to do for childcare,

00:40:27.280 --> 00:40:30.430
it goes away after
18 years, right?

00:40:30.430 --> 00:40:33.250
Eventually you don't have
that as a problem any longer.

00:40:39.430 --> 00:40:41.270
And then they bring
their munchkin,

00:40:41.270 --> 00:40:43.700
and then you're the
childcare for their munchkin.

00:40:43.700 --> 00:40:47.550
So the masters are doing
some really amazing things.

00:40:47.550 --> 00:40:49.290
When they have a
conflict conversation,

00:40:49.290 --> 00:40:52.490
if you can take these skills
home, this would be fantastic.

00:40:52.490 --> 00:40:55.060
Number one, the skill
that the masters are doing

00:40:55.060 --> 00:40:57.590
is that they're bringing up
a complaint, which is OK.

00:40:57.590 --> 00:40:59.600
To criticize is not OK.

00:40:59.600 --> 00:41:01.830
They're bringing it up
in a really gentle way.

00:41:01.830 --> 00:41:04.770
They're incredibly skillful.

00:41:04.770 --> 00:41:08.150
Think of it as, like, putting
on the art of manipulation.

00:41:08.150 --> 00:41:10.640
How can I bring
this complaint up

00:41:10.640 --> 00:41:12.980
in a way in which my
partner is going to hear me

00:41:12.980 --> 00:41:16.560
and is going to be willing
to work with me on this?

00:41:16.560 --> 00:41:19.050
And if it's a sure
fire way to blow it,

00:41:19.050 --> 00:41:22.330
you can bring it up by saying,
you always or you never.

00:41:22.330 --> 00:41:23.100
Right?

00:41:23.100 --> 00:41:26.470
How many times does you always
and you never end right?

00:41:26.470 --> 00:41:29.260
How many times do you actually
get your partner to say,

00:41:29.260 --> 00:41:31.140
you know what, you're
absolutely right.

00:41:31.140 --> 00:41:32.980
I am always a slob.

00:41:32.980 --> 00:41:35.894
I am always doing this.

00:41:35.894 --> 00:41:37.810
So if you want to blow
it, start it like that.

00:41:37.810 --> 00:41:39.790
But if you don't, you
bring your complaint

00:41:39.790 --> 00:41:42.070
up by using I
statements and you're

00:41:42.070 --> 00:41:44.760
describing what's going on
in a non-judgmental way.

00:41:44.760 --> 00:41:48.310
You know, honey, I notice that
there's clothes next to the bed

00:41:48.310 --> 00:41:49.080
again.

00:41:49.080 --> 00:41:53.140
And I would really
appreciate it if you

00:41:53.140 --> 00:41:57.390
could undress next to the hamper
rather than undressing next

00:41:57.390 --> 00:41:58.410
to the bed.

00:41:58.410 --> 00:42:00.654
Do you think maybe
you could do that?

00:42:00.654 --> 00:42:02.070
It's pretty gentle,
you think he'd

00:42:02.070 --> 00:42:05.300
be willing to give it a
shot at least that night?

00:42:05.300 --> 00:42:06.520
Yeah?

00:42:06.520 --> 00:42:10.870
Poor guy, he gets thrown
under the bus so much.

00:42:10.870 --> 00:42:14.090
What is something else
that the masters are doing?

00:42:14.090 --> 00:42:15.960
So here's an
interesting statistic.

00:42:15.960 --> 00:42:18.730
Dr. Gottman can tell
how a conversation is

00:42:18.730 --> 00:42:20.580
going to end by how it starts.

00:42:20.580 --> 00:42:22.410
So he watches the
first three minutes

00:42:22.410 --> 00:42:23.740
of a conflict conversation.

00:42:23.740 --> 00:42:25.900
He says, oh yeah, I know
how that's going to end.

00:42:25.900 --> 00:42:26.680
You know how?

00:42:26.680 --> 00:42:29.830
96% of the time,
if it starts off

00:42:29.830 --> 00:42:32.360
gentle and kind, it will
end gentle and kind.

00:42:32.360 --> 00:42:36.510
If you want to get what you
want, ask for it in a nice way.

00:42:36.510 --> 00:42:38.980
I mean, that's kind of
a no brainer, right?

00:42:38.980 --> 00:42:42.230
But that's not
always what happens.

00:42:42.230 --> 00:42:46.160
Here's another thing
about the first skill.

00:42:46.160 --> 00:42:47.660
Who do you think
is most often going

00:42:47.660 --> 00:42:49.640
to bring up conflict in
a relationship, the man

00:42:49.640 --> 00:42:52.066
or the woman?

00:42:52.066 --> 00:42:53.290
It's the woman, yeah.

00:42:53.290 --> 00:42:55.606
You were like.

00:42:55.606 --> 00:42:57.240
Yes, it is the woman.

00:42:57.240 --> 00:42:59.930
Most of the time, the
female is going to complain.

00:42:59.930 --> 00:43:04.750
And that's absolutely true.

00:43:04.750 --> 00:43:08.170
Skill number two, people
who are starting a conflict

00:43:08.170 --> 00:43:11.460
conversation, they are
making repairs all the time.

00:43:11.460 --> 00:43:14.420
So you may start off with
a you always or you never,

00:43:14.420 --> 00:43:16.920
but that doesn't mean that
you have to be doomed.

00:43:16.920 --> 00:43:20.190
You can make repair and you can
turn that conversation around.

00:43:20.190 --> 00:43:22.720
So if you imagine
being a truck driver,

00:43:22.720 --> 00:43:24.220
have you ever seen
those ramps where

00:43:24.220 --> 00:43:25.900
the trucks when they
lose their brakes,

00:43:25.900 --> 00:43:27.570
they have to go up the ramp?

00:43:27.570 --> 00:43:29.670
That's sort of what
a repair attempt is.

00:43:29.670 --> 00:43:33.260
It's using that ramp to stop
the trajectory, and the speed,

00:43:33.260 --> 00:43:35.595
and the momentum of
the conversation.

00:43:35.595 --> 00:43:37.720
So you're using a repair
attempt and you're saying,

00:43:37.720 --> 00:43:41.540
you know what, I really think
we're going off track here.

00:43:41.540 --> 00:43:43.380
I think I need to start over.

00:43:43.380 --> 00:43:45.350
Or you know what,
I'm really sorry, I

00:43:45.350 --> 00:43:48.520
used a blaming statement there,
I'd like to turn this around.

00:43:48.520 --> 00:43:53.230
So there is an entire
sheet of repair attempts.

00:43:53.230 --> 00:43:55.330
And it feels a little
weird at first.

00:43:55.330 --> 00:43:56.830
And when I say
entire sheet, there's

00:43:56.830 --> 00:43:59.700
an entire page of
repair attempts in here

00:43:59.700 --> 00:44:03.640
that you can use when you start
to notice that the conversation

00:44:03.640 --> 00:44:04.910
is getting derailed.

00:44:04.910 --> 00:44:08.130
What makes the repair
attempts so powerful

00:44:08.130 --> 00:44:10.990
is whether or not you have
that foundation of friendship.

00:44:10.990 --> 00:44:13.690
So you can use a repair
attempt, but your partner

00:44:13.690 --> 00:44:16.280
won't hear that unless you
have a strong foundation

00:44:16.280 --> 00:44:19.090
of a friendship, which
is why Dr. Gottman said

00:44:19.090 --> 00:44:21.220
it's so important.

00:44:21.220 --> 00:44:22.760
So if you're using
a repair attempt,

00:44:22.760 --> 00:44:26.628
I use this as an example.

00:44:26.628 --> 00:44:30.767
Two of my friends are driving
in a car, I'm in the backseat.

00:44:30.767 --> 00:44:33.100
They bicker back and forth,
they're going, going, going.

00:44:33.100 --> 00:44:35.350
I'm not paying any attention,
I'm probably on Facebook

00:44:35.350 --> 00:44:36.220
on my phone.

00:44:36.220 --> 00:44:39.160
And all of a sudden,
the car gets silent.

00:44:39.160 --> 00:44:43.000
And I look up and I notice that
the driver is staring straight

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:45.920
ahead, passenger is
staring out the window.

00:44:45.920 --> 00:44:51.210
And me as a couples therapist,
I'm like, ooh, this is juicy.

00:44:51.210 --> 00:44:53.280
What's going to happen?

00:44:53.280 --> 00:44:56.770
So about 30 seconds go by and
the tension is really high.

00:44:56.770 --> 00:44:59.350
And then all a sudden,
passenger turns around

00:44:59.350 --> 00:45:03.850
and licks the driver from
his jaw up to his ear.

00:45:03.850 --> 00:45:06.350
It's disgusting, right?

00:45:06.350 --> 00:45:08.130
But do you know what that was?

00:45:08.130 --> 00:45:09.810
It was a repair attempt.

00:45:09.810 --> 00:45:10.650
Believe it or not.

00:45:10.650 --> 00:45:13.280
So a repair attempt
is anything that you

00:45:13.280 --> 00:45:15.400
do to take something
that's getting

00:45:15.400 --> 00:45:20.230
derailed, a conversation, an
interaction, and change it.

00:45:20.230 --> 00:45:23.190
Did he accept the
repair attempt?

00:45:23.190 --> 00:45:24.040
Absolutely.

00:45:24.040 --> 00:45:24.840
How could you not?

00:45:24.840 --> 00:45:27.310
How could you ignore
a lick on the face?

00:45:27.310 --> 00:45:30.320
Anyway, I digress.

00:45:30.320 --> 00:45:34.650
You can make repair attempts,
but what makes it most potent

00:45:34.650 --> 00:45:37.090
is whether or not you have
that friendship foundation

00:45:37.090 --> 00:45:41.125
and whether or not your
partner accepts your repair.

00:45:41.125 --> 00:45:43.680
OK, so we talked about flooding
a little bit when we were

00:45:43.680 --> 00:45:45.000
talking about stonewalling.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:46.416
What ends up
happening when you're

00:45:46.416 --> 00:45:48.170
getting emotionally flooded?

00:45:48.170 --> 00:45:52.520
So being emotionally flooded
can feel a lot of different ways

00:45:52.520 --> 00:45:53.900
for different people.

00:45:53.900 --> 00:45:55.554
You can get a tightness
in your chest.

00:45:55.554 --> 00:45:57.220
So imagine that you're
having a conflict

00:45:57.220 --> 00:46:01.160
conversation with your partner
and it's really, really

00:46:01.160 --> 00:46:01.780
going bad.

00:46:01.780 --> 00:46:04.890
In your head, you're thinking,
oh no, not this again.

00:46:04.890 --> 00:46:07.920
And maybe your
partner just thinks

00:46:07.920 --> 00:46:11.680
if I just raise my voice, he'll
hear me eventually, right?

00:46:11.680 --> 00:46:14.390
Or maybe I should just
throw a few things

00:46:14.390 --> 00:46:15.530
to get his attention.

00:46:15.530 --> 00:46:19.020
So you might start to feel
physiologically aroused.

00:46:19.020 --> 00:46:22.860
So your heart starts beating,
your face might feel flushed,

00:46:22.860 --> 00:46:25.085
you might start sweating a lot.

00:46:25.085 --> 00:46:27.740
Or maybe you start
to get tunnel vision.

00:46:27.740 --> 00:46:30.440
Have you ever had road rage
so bad where you literally

00:46:30.440 --> 00:46:33.176
didn't, I mean, it's Seattle,
so I'm sure all of us

00:46:33.176 --> 00:46:34.550
have had road rage
at some point.

00:46:34.550 --> 00:46:38.920
But where you almost feel
as if, like, you lose vision

00:46:38.920 --> 00:46:43.090
or you can't hear any longer or
your heart is just pounding out

00:46:43.090 --> 00:46:44.070
of your chest?

00:46:44.070 --> 00:46:46.170
That's what it feels
like to be flooded.

00:46:46.170 --> 00:46:49.350
But the masters are
recognizing before they

00:46:49.350 --> 00:46:53.510
get flooded that they need
to do some psychological and

00:46:53.510 --> 00:46:55.850
physiological self-soothing,
which means that they're

00:46:55.850 --> 00:46:58.243
stopping the conversation.

00:46:58.243 --> 00:47:00.275
Now this feels a little
weird for some people.

00:47:00.275 --> 00:47:01.650
Well, if we stop
the conversation

00:47:01.650 --> 00:47:03.240
we'll never get back to it.

00:47:03.240 --> 00:47:05.660
The rule of thumb is if
we stop the conversation,

00:47:05.660 --> 00:47:08.170
we're coming back
to it in 20 minutes.

00:47:08.170 --> 00:47:10.980
So one of you indicates I'm
feeling, I'm feeling flooded,

00:47:10.980 --> 00:47:12.380
we need to take a break.

00:47:12.380 --> 00:47:14.225
And they go their separate ways.

00:47:14.225 --> 00:47:16.630
In order to take a break
where your body is going

00:47:16.630 --> 00:47:19.960
to be able to self-soothe
and relax and come back down,

00:47:19.960 --> 00:47:21.650
you have to leave
your partner's sight.

00:47:21.650 --> 00:47:24.640
So it's not the two of you
sitting in silence staring

00:47:24.640 --> 00:47:25.990
at each other.

00:47:25.990 --> 00:47:29.790
You have to change the course
of where your mind is going.

00:47:29.790 --> 00:47:32.180
So you have to think about
something that's pleasing.

00:47:32.180 --> 00:47:36.166
This is not an opportunity
to formulate your rebuttal.

00:47:36.166 --> 00:47:37.540
So you're going
to start thinking

00:47:37.540 --> 00:47:42.160
about ponies and rainbows and
all those wonderful things.

00:47:42.160 --> 00:47:43.920
So I'm just curious,
for you guys,

00:47:43.920 --> 00:47:46.170
what do you do to calm down?

00:47:46.170 --> 00:47:48.320
What do you do to soothe?

00:47:48.320 --> 00:47:51.632
You go for a walk?

00:47:51.632 --> 00:47:52.531
Walk the dog?

00:47:52.531 --> 00:47:53.031
Facebook?

00:47:55.620 --> 00:47:57.400
I know, I do it too.

00:47:57.400 --> 00:48:01.530
Clean, take a shower, work out.

00:48:01.530 --> 00:48:02.920
What's that?

00:48:02.920 --> 00:48:03.420
Cook?

00:48:03.420 --> 00:48:05.250
Awesome, come to my house.

00:48:05.250 --> 00:48:07.570
We'll all cook together.

00:48:07.570 --> 00:48:08.070
Yeah.

00:48:08.070 --> 00:48:09.670
So you're going to
do something that

00:48:09.670 --> 00:48:11.870
is soothing for 20
minutes, and then you're

00:48:11.870 --> 00:48:13.890
going to come back
to the conversation.

00:48:13.890 --> 00:48:16.270
And by that point, here's
the interesting part.

00:48:16.270 --> 00:48:17.860
Why is it that we're
taking a break?

00:48:17.860 --> 00:48:21.640
What is it about flooding
that you have to take a break?

00:48:21.640 --> 00:48:24.250
It's because you're no longer
using your prefrontal cortex.

00:48:24.250 --> 00:48:26.570
You literally flip your lid.

00:48:26.570 --> 00:48:29.810
Your body says I'm
in fight or flight,

00:48:29.810 --> 00:48:32.110
I can't use my
prefrontal cortex,

00:48:32.110 --> 00:48:33.980
I need to use my
reptilian brain now

00:48:33.980 --> 00:48:36.280
because this is
going to save me.

00:48:36.280 --> 00:48:38.320
So now you're using
the back of your brain

00:48:38.320 --> 00:48:40.490
and you're not able to
have a conversation that

00:48:40.490 --> 00:48:42.310
is logical with your partner.

00:48:42.310 --> 00:48:43.890
What ends up happening
and why people

00:48:43.890 --> 00:48:46.420
get hurt so badly in
conversations where

00:48:46.420 --> 00:48:48.420
they are flooded
is that they keep

00:48:48.420 --> 00:48:51.260
trying to have the conversation,
but they're no longer

00:48:51.260 --> 00:48:52.585
using logic or reason.

00:48:52.585 --> 00:48:54.800
Has anybody seen
that YouTube clip,

00:48:54.800 --> 00:48:58.140
it's these two one-year-old
babies, they're twin boys.

00:48:58.140 --> 00:49:00.390
They're in the kitchen,
they're both in diapers,

00:49:00.390 --> 00:49:03.680
and they're talking to
each other in baby babble.

00:49:03.680 --> 00:49:07.400
And one's going blah, blah, blah
and then the other one, blah,

00:49:07.400 --> 00:49:08.970
blah, blah, blah.

00:49:08.970 --> 00:49:12.150
That's what it looks like when
two adults are physiologically

00:49:12.150 --> 00:49:15.080
flooded, is there's
nothing going on up here.

00:49:15.080 --> 00:49:18.500
It's just babble at that point.

00:49:18.500 --> 00:49:24.290
So any questions about
self-soothing or flooding?

00:49:24.290 --> 00:49:26.630
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:32.570 --> 00:49:33.570
LAURA HECK: Yeah.

00:49:33.570 --> 00:49:34.445
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:37.160 --> 00:49:39.190
LAURA HECK: So what do
you do when you come back

00:49:39.190 --> 00:49:41.230
from your break and
your partner doesn't

00:49:41.230 --> 00:49:43.210
want to discuss it anymore?

00:49:43.210 --> 00:49:45.200
It has to be an agreement.

00:49:45.200 --> 00:49:47.085
There has to be an
agreement that if you're

00:49:47.085 --> 00:49:49.460
going to have this conversation
and one of you is feeling

00:49:49.460 --> 00:49:51.150
flooded and needs
to take a break,

00:49:51.150 --> 00:49:53.710
that it has to be an
agreement to come back to it.

00:49:53.710 --> 00:49:56.230
Because if it's a conflict,
if it's important to you

00:49:56.230 --> 00:49:59.255
to solve the problem, it's
important to both of you.

00:49:59.255 --> 00:50:00.870
So it needs to be
a conversation.

00:50:00.870 --> 00:50:03.650
But sometimes your partner
may say, I'm still flooded

00:50:03.650 --> 00:50:05.236
or I'm really hurt.

00:50:05.236 --> 00:50:06.610
And at that point,
maybe you need

00:50:06.610 --> 00:50:09.680
to do some repairing in order
to get back to the point

00:50:09.680 --> 00:50:12.770
where you want to have
that conversation again.

00:50:12.770 --> 00:50:14.730
I think one of the
common misconceptions

00:50:14.730 --> 00:50:17.230
is the idea don't
go to bed angry.

00:50:17.230 --> 00:50:19.110
This is actually really harmful.

00:50:19.110 --> 00:50:21.250
Because if you are so
worked up and you're

00:50:21.250 --> 00:50:23.880
trying to solve the problem
and you're no longer using

00:50:23.880 --> 00:50:26.500
your prefrontal cortex, now
you're in your reptilian brain,

00:50:26.500 --> 00:50:28.625
but all you want to have
to do is solve the problem

00:50:28.625 --> 00:50:30.180
because we have
to go to bed, you

00:50:30.180 --> 00:50:32.029
end up exhausted the next day.

00:50:32.029 --> 00:50:33.320
You haven't solved the problem.

00:50:33.320 --> 00:50:35.310
And now you don't like
your partner anymore.

00:50:35.310 --> 00:50:36.390
So go to bed.

00:50:36.390 --> 00:50:37.790
Take a nap.

00:50:37.790 --> 00:50:40.740
Do what you need to do so
that you come back to it.

00:50:40.740 --> 00:50:44.490
Not all arguments or conflicts
will be solved in the moment.

00:50:44.490 --> 00:50:47.420
It might take a couple of days
to work through a conflict.

00:50:47.420 --> 00:50:49.830
But being able to respect
when your partner is flooded

00:50:49.830 --> 00:50:54.880
is number one, and recognize
that they need to self-soothe.

00:50:54.880 --> 00:50:57.280
OK.

00:50:57.280 --> 00:51:00.020
So what do you do if you
do have a solvable problem?

00:51:00.020 --> 00:51:02.300
31% of those solvable problems.

00:51:02.300 --> 00:51:05.380
How do you actually go
through to solve them?

00:51:05.380 --> 00:51:07.060
This is something
that we recommend

00:51:07.060 --> 00:51:09.840
is that you draw these
circles on a piece of paper

00:51:09.840 --> 00:51:13.880
and the circle in the inside
is your inflexible area.

00:51:13.880 --> 00:51:16.650
So let's just pick
a solvable problem.

00:51:16.650 --> 00:51:17.880
What are we going to solve?

00:51:17.880 --> 00:51:20.590
Car?

00:51:20.590 --> 00:51:23.380
So my husband wants
to get, what's that?

00:51:23.380 --> 00:51:25.062
What movie to see?

00:51:25.062 --> 00:51:26.770
I need something that's
a little juicier.

00:51:29.580 --> 00:51:32.500
I'm going to go with car
just because it sort of has

00:51:32.500 --> 00:51:34.460
some value systems around money.

00:51:34.460 --> 00:51:39.950
So let's say that my husband
wants to get the new Tesla that

00:51:39.950 --> 00:51:42.570
just came out.

00:51:42.570 --> 00:51:48.670
And I want to buy the
used minivan for $5,000.

00:51:48.670 --> 00:51:51.360
You're giggling,
but that happened.

00:51:54.720 --> 00:51:58.440
So what's happening is the
two of us need a new vehicle

00:51:58.440 --> 00:52:00.410
and he wants to get the Tesla.

00:52:00.410 --> 00:52:02.050
I don't even know
how much Teslas run,

00:52:02.050 --> 00:52:04.100
but they're expensive, right?

00:52:04.100 --> 00:52:05.510
So he wants to
get the new Tesla,

00:52:05.510 --> 00:52:07.100
I want to get the minivan.

00:52:07.100 --> 00:52:09.664
It's all sort of
grounded in money.

00:52:09.664 --> 00:52:10.830
I kind of have money issues.

00:52:10.830 --> 00:52:12.770
I'm the saver, he's the spender.

00:52:12.770 --> 00:52:14.550
That's a perpetual
problem that comes up

00:52:14.550 --> 00:52:16.380
a lot in relationships.

00:52:16.380 --> 00:52:19.370
But we need to actually solve
it because we need a vehicle.

00:52:19.370 --> 00:52:21.850
So my areas of
inflexibility are going

00:52:21.850 --> 00:52:26.080
to be the areas that if I was
to compromise on these issues,

00:52:26.080 --> 00:52:27.800
it would feel as
if I was breaking

00:52:27.800 --> 00:52:30.960
the bones of my own body because
it was so tied of my values

00:52:30.960 --> 00:52:33.160
system, so tied to
my worldview, so tied

00:52:33.160 --> 00:52:37.020
to who I am as a human being
that if I was to compromise,

00:52:37.020 --> 00:52:41.210
I would have the same argument
with him two months from now.

00:52:41.210 --> 00:52:42.960
So I'm going to write
in the center circle

00:52:42.960 --> 00:52:47.140
that I think it is incredibly
important that we only

00:52:47.140 --> 00:52:48.740
pay cash for cars.

00:52:48.740 --> 00:52:50.980
That's just a value system.

00:52:50.980 --> 00:52:52.490
Dave Ramsey taught me that.

00:52:52.490 --> 00:52:57.840
So he's going to put
in his inner circle

00:52:57.840 --> 00:53:03.660
that his core need, his
core desire is tied to,

00:53:03.660 --> 00:53:06.505
what would be my husband's
core need for this,

00:53:06.505 --> 00:53:11.300
I was going to say to look
cool, but maybe his core need

00:53:11.300 --> 00:53:14.900
is that he's worked really,
really hard to become a VP

00:53:14.900 --> 00:53:17.360
and now that he's there,
he needs a car that

00:53:17.360 --> 00:53:19.780
also represents that he's a VP.

00:53:19.780 --> 00:53:24.080
So maybe that's his core need,
is like this feeling of status

00:53:24.080 --> 00:53:28.070
or this feeling of
needing to reward himself

00:53:28.070 --> 00:53:29.420
for his hard work.

00:53:29.420 --> 00:53:33.180
So now that we have our core
areas of inflexibility, now

00:53:33.180 --> 00:53:35.760
we're going to talk about what
the areas of flexibility are.

00:53:35.760 --> 00:53:39.780
So my area of flexibility
is I'm flexible on the color

00:53:39.780 --> 00:53:44.180
of the car, I'm flexible
on whether or not

00:53:44.180 --> 00:53:46.475
it's four wheel drive, I'm
flexible whether or not

00:53:46.475 --> 00:53:48.100
we don't get a minivan,
it doesn't have

00:53:48.100 --> 00:53:49.980
to do with the sliding door.

00:53:49.980 --> 00:53:53.260
But maybe my area
of inflexibility

00:53:53.260 --> 00:53:55.840
might be that I don't want to
spend any more than $30,000

00:53:55.840 --> 00:53:57.170
on a car.

00:53:57.170 --> 00:54:01.450
So then he's like, oh
boy, that Tesla's not

00:54:01.450 --> 00:54:04.240
happening any time soon.

00:54:04.240 --> 00:54:06.600
So this is how you
find common ground.

00:54:06.600 --> 00:54:09.780
The most important piece
about this exercise

00:54:09.780 --> 00:54:12.760
is that the two of
you are putting down

00:54:12.760 --> 00:54:15.110
the pieces that are
most important to you

00:54:15.110 --> 00:54:17.080
and those are sort
of like, we're

00:54:17.080 --> 00:54:18.780
not willing to yield on these.

00:54:18.780 --> 00:54:20.940
Being willing to
yield is important,

00:54:20.940 --> 00:54:25.330
but the inner circle,
it's small for a reason.

00:54:25.330 --> 00:54:27.940
You don't want to have too
many areas of inflexibility.

00:54:27.940 --> 00:54:30.280
The goal is wanting to
compromise with your partner.

00:54:30.280 --> 00:54:33.200
But if you indicate
what areas it is

00:54:33.200 --> 00:54:34.820
that if you were
to yield on it, it

00:54:34.820 --> 00:54:37.170
would feel as if you're
breaking your own bones,

00:54:37.170 --> 00:54:40.480
why would you want to compromise
your partner's values in order

00:54:40.480 --> 00:54:44.050
to get what you want?

00:54:44.050 --> 00:54:45.595
Any steps about this area?

00:54:48.306 --> 00:54:52.090
OK, so now we're
at principle six.

00:54:52.090 --> 00:54:56.310
We've gone through some of
the friendship foundation.

00:54:56.310 --> 00:55:01.070
We've talked a little bit
about yielding to your partner.

00:55:01.070 --> 00:55:03.180
Now we're overcoming gridlock.

00:55:03.180 --> 00:55:05.330
So there's perpetual
problems in the relationship

00:55:05.330 --> 00:55:08.350
and there are solvable
problems in the relationship.

00:55:08.350 --> 00:55:10.700
But sometimes you get
really gridlocked.

00:55:10.700 --> 00:55:13.420
You know that you're feeling
gridlocked on an issue

00:55:13.420 --> 00:55:16.360
because every time it
comes up, all of a sudden,

00:55:16.360 --> 00:55:18.550
you feel like oh,
not this again.

00:55:18.550 --> 00:55:21.710
Or you go from 0
to 60 within, like,

00:55:21.710 --> 00:55:23.840
two seconds of talking
about that topic.

00:55:23.840 --> 00:55:27.020
Or you feel even more
polarized, like you started off

00:55:27.020 --> 00:55:29.920
pretty close, you were
almost willing to negotiate,

00:55:29.920 --> 00:55:31.610
but now that you're
gridlocked, you guys

00:55:31.610 --> 00:55:34.000
are on total opposite ends.

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:35.500
You lose your sense
of humor, you're

00:55:35.500 --> 00:55:38.460
no longer willing to
negotiate with your partner.

00:55:38.460 --> 00:55:40.100
What do you do?

00:55:40.100 --> 00:55:43.050
The masters figured
out that in order

00:55:43.050 --> 00:55:45.590
to overcome gridlock
in relationships,

00:55:45.590 --> 00:55:49.660
you have to suspend the
desire to solve that problem

00:55:49.660 --> 00:55:52.170
and see from your
partner's perspective.

00:55:52.170 --> 00:55:54.210
We call this empathy.

00:55:54.210 --> 00:55:56.400
So one of the things
that couples can do

00:55:56.400 --> 00:55:59.210
is that you can sit on
opposite sides of the couch

00:55:59.210 --> 00:56:01.110
and you can say, I
understand that we're

00:56:01.110 --> 00:56:03.970
pretty gridlocked on
this issue, and I'm

00:56:03.970 --> 00:56:05.850
willing to hear
your perspective.

00:56:05.850 --> 00:56:07.710
In every argument
and disagreement

00:56:07.710 --> 00:56:08.990
there are two perspectives.

00:56:08.990 --> 00:56:12.600
Both of them are correct,
both of them are right.

00:56:12.600 --> 00:56:15.670
You feel so strongly
about this side

00:56:15.670 --> 00:56:18.120
and he feels so
strongly about this side

00:56:18.120 --> 00:56:21.780
that you have to be willing
to understand what is it,

00:56:21.780 --> 00:56:25.670
why are you so, why are
you so focused on this?

00:56:25.670 --> 00:56:27.090
Why is this so important?

00:56:27.090 --> 00:56:29.030
And if you're willing
to hear your partner

00:56:29.030 --> 00:56:32.330
and they're willing to
hear you, suddenly you

00:56:32.330 --> 00:56:35.950
have much more respect for where
your partner's perspective is

00:56:35.950 --> 00:56:38.470
coming from.

00:56:38.470 --> 00:56:40.980
So what we ask for couples
to do is they take turns.

00:56:40.980 --> 00:56:42.830
One couple will
start off, and you'll

00:56:42.830 --> 00:56:45.720
ask questions like, tell me why
this is so important to you.

00:56:45.720 --> 00:56:50.280
Tell me why you are so
focused on this one thing.

00:56:50.280 --> 00:56:51.800
I'm really curious.

00:56:51.800 --> 00:56:54.650
You're suspending judgment,
you're suspending the desire

00:56:54.650 --> 00:56:57.870
to solve the problem, and all
you're doing is listening.

00:56:57.870 --> 00:57:00.450
It's incredible
when you see people

00:57:00.450 --> 00:57:04.460
who are fighting, if you
give them the opportunity

00:57:04.460 --> 00:57:08.710
to just state their perspective
in full without someone

00:57:08.710 --> 00:57:13.150
interjecting or poking
holes in them, how amazing

00:57:13.150 --> 00:57:15.810
that starts to
de-escalate everything.

00:57:15.810 --> 00:57:17.770
So one partner takes turns.

00:57:17.770 --> 00:57:19.040
Maybe it's 10 minutes.

00:57:19.040 --> 00:57:20.670
And all you do is just listen.

00:57:20.670 --> 00:57:21.920
Tell me your perspective.

00:57:21.920 --> 00:57:25.120
From your perspective,
why is this important?

00:57:25.120 --> 00:57:28.210
And when they're done, you
state back and you say,

00:57:28.210 --> 00:57:30.940
so this is what I think
is your perspective,

00:57:30.940 --> 00:57:33.530
this is what I hear you
saying, and then you swap.

00:57:33.530 --> 00:57:36.590
And the other person gets
to share their perspective.

00:57:36.590 --> 00:57:39.400
Did you solve the problem?

00:57:39.400 --> 00:57:40.100
Not at all.

00:57:40.100 --> 00:57:42.124
All you did was
had the opportunity

00:57:42.124 --> 00:57:43.790
to share why it was
so important to you.

00:57:47.485 --> 00:57:50.390
This is the last
and final principle,

00:57:50.390 --> 00:57:53.430
and then you all can
leave me for the day.

00:57:53.430 --> 00:57:56.720
So once you have
learned to master

00:57:56.720 --> 00:57:58.420
a friendship in
your relationship

00:57:58.420 --> 00:58:01.720
and you have learned to
master how to solve conflict

00:58:01.720 --> 00:58:05.080
in a healthy way,
the final way is

00:58:05.080 --> 00:58:07.430
to create meaning in
your relationship.

00:58:07.430 --> 00:58:12.430
So couples come in and they
say, is this all that there is.

00:58:12.430 --> 00:58:14.610
We just procreate,
we have babies,

00:58:14.610 --> 00:58:18.810
we see family and
friends on the weekends.

00:58:18.810 --> 00:58:20.680
And is this really all there is?

00:58:20.680 --> 00:58:21.930
I go to work, I come home.

00:58:21.930 --> 00:58:23.430
Like, it feels like
we're roommates.

00:58:23.430 --> 00:58:27.080
There's nothing really
substantial to our relationship

00:58:27.080 --> 00:58:28.300
that's creating meaning.

00:58:28.300 --> 00:58:32.290
And Dr. Gottman found that
for healthy, happy, thriving

00:58:32.290 --> 00:58:33.710
couples, they're
creating meaning

00:58:33.710 --> 00:58:35.260
in a lot of different ways.

00:58:35.260 --> 00:58:39.110
They're moving
from I or me to we.

00:58:39.110 --> 00:58:41.920
And the way that you create
we in your relationship

00:58:41.920 --> 00:58:44.050
is to look at
these four pillars.

00:58:44.050 --> 00:58:45.820
Number one is rituals.

00:58:45.820 --> 00:58:48.350
You can create rituals
in your relationship that

00:58:48.350 --> 00:58:51.250
create beautiful meaning,
but more importantly, it

00:58:51.250 --> 00:58:52.720
creates an
opportunity to connect

00:58:52.720 --> 00:58:55.300
on a really reliable
time and space.

00:58:55.300 --> 00:58:58.600
So a ritual in our
household is in the morning,

00:58:58.600 --> 00:59:01.610
when my baby wakes, up
husband hears the baby

00:59:01.610 --> 00:59:04.570
and me waking up, and he
brings me up a cup of coffee.

00:59:04.570 --> 00:59:07.450
And we play in the big
family bed for 10 minutes.

00:59:07.450 --> 00:59:08.290
It's wonderful.

00:59:08.290 --> 00:59:10.960
I look forward to it,
he looks forward to it.

00:59:10.960 --> 00:59:13.970
I feel cared for and we
have connected first thing

00:59:13.970 --> 00:59:15.390
in the morning.

00:59:15.390 --> 00:59:18.640
Another ritual that I
really like is one partner,

00:59:18.640 --> 00:59:23.140
I had a couple come to me and
they started every evening,

00:59:23.140 --> 00:59:26.710
once the kids went to bed,
he would put the tea kettle

00:59:26.710 --> 00:59:27.610
on the stove.

00:59:27.610 --> 00:59:30.130
And by the time it was
done and whistling,

00:59:30.130 --> 00:59:32.260
the wife would come
in and they would

00:59:32.260 --> 00:59:34.370
sit on opposite
sides of the couch

00:59:34.370 --> 00:59:36.630
and they would sip on
their tea, and they

00:59:36.630 --> 00:59:39.870
would massage each other's feet
and catch up about the day.

00:59:39.870 --> 00:59:40.370
Right?

00:59:40.370 --> 00:59:42.180
How many of you would like that?

00:59:42.180 --> 00:59:44.720
So that's a ritual that
they are looking forward to.

00:59:44.720 --> 00:59:47.860
It's something that's unique and
special to their relationship.

00:59:47.860 --> 00:59:50.750
But it's also something
that they have as a time

00:59:50.750 --> 00:59:53.463
that they can connect
every single day.

00:59:53.463 --> 00:59:54.230
Roles.

00:59:54.230 --> 00:59:56.900
How do you make roles
unique and special

00:59:56.900 --> 00:59:59.350
in the family within
this relationship?

00:59:59.350 --> 01:00:01.540
You can ask one another,
what do you want

01:00:01.540 --> 01:00:03.700
your role as husband to be?

01:00:03.700 --> 01:00:05.790
Like, what did you
envision as a husband?

01:00:05.790 --> 01:00:09.430
Did you envision being
the emotional person

01:00:09.430 --> 01:00:11.210
in the relationship
or did you envision

01:00:11.210 --> 01:00:13.060
providing for the family?

01:00:13.060 --> 01:00:16.980
And if that's what you envision,
how can we make this happen?

01:00:16.980 --> 01:00:21.420
Or a role in the family might
be that you're the caretaker.

01:00:21.420 --> 01:00:23.590
So every time somebody
gets sick, and this is true

01:00:23.590 --> 01:00:24.420
in my family.

01:00:24.420 --> 01:00:27.050
I'm not the
caretaker, by the way.

01:00:27.050 --> 01:00:30.630
But I have a step-mom
and she's incredible.

01:00:30.630 --> 01:00:32.600
She is the caretaker
for the entire block.

01:00:32.600 --> 01:00:35.430
That was something that is
unique and special for her.

01:00:35.430 --> 01:00:38.210
And everybody embraces that.

01:00:38.210 --> 01:00:39.800
So she takes care of everybody.

01:00:39.800 --> 01:00:42.400
When somebody gets
sick, they are pampered.

01:00:42.400 --> 01:00:45.650
They have the special blankie,
they have the Neti pot,

01:00:45.650 --> 01:00:47.400
they have, like, feet warmers.

01:00:47.400 --> 01:00:48.960
I mean, she goes
above and beyond.

01:00:48.960 --> 01:00:52.120
But that's a role that is really
special to her that has created

01:00:52.120 --> 01:00:54.970
meaning in their relationship.

01:00:54.970 --> 01:00:57.460
Common goals.

01:00:57.460 --> 01:01:00.276
You know where John and
Julie Gottman are right now?

01:01:00.276 --> 01:01:03.070
They're hiking, they're
actually backpacking.

01:01:03.070 --> 01:01:07.790
For those of you that don't
know, John is in his 70s now

01:01:07.790 --> 01:01:10.020
and Julie loves to hike.

01:01:10.020 --> 01:01:11.560
And that's something
that she does.

01:01:11.560 --> 01:01:14.070
And John likes to say that
he's not willing to go anywhere

01:01:14.070 --> 01:01:17.130
unless there's room service.

01:01:17.130 --> 01:01:19.890
But John's hiking, which
is pretty incredible.

01:01:19.890 --> 01:01:22.260
So they have this common goal.

01:01:22.260 --> 01:01:26.980
And he's joining Julie on this
goal that she has of hiking.

01:01:26.980 --> 01:01:30.710
Even more is that when John
and Julie met each other,

01:01:30.710 --> 01:01:33.040
Julie had this
goal, I want to help

01:01:33.040 --> 01:01:34.790
as many couples as possible.

01:01:34.790 --> 01:01:37.600
John had the research,
Julie had the know how.

01:01:37.600 --> 01:01:40.250
They came together and
they created a special goal

01:01:40.250 --> 01:01:41.920
and meaning around
their relationship

01:01:41.920 --> 01:01:43.670
that they are going
to touch as many lives

01:01:43.670 --> 01:01:47.022
possible, and look at them now.

01:01:47.022 --> 01:01:49.090
So the final pillar
is symbols, and this

01:01:49.090 --> 01:01:51.940
would be things that have shared
meaning in your relationship.

01:01:51.940 --> 01:01:55.750
It might be a cross, it
might be a family portrait,

01:01:55.750 --> 01:01:57.880
but it's a tangible
item that has

01:01:57.880 --> 01:02:01.120
meaning of the we
within the relationship.

01:02:01.120 --> 01:02:03.650
So Dr. Gottman says
that this is really

01:02:03.650 --> 01:02:06.040
like the top of the house,
that once you have built

01:02:06.040 --> 01:02:09.290
this foundation and the
pillars of this relationship,

01:02:09.290 --> 01:02:10.960
creating shared
meaning is really

01:02:10.960 --> 01:02:12.140
like the top of the house.

01:02:12.140 --> 01:02:14.320
And thus, there are
the seven principles

01:02:14.320 --> 01:02:16.700
for making your marriage work.

01:02:16.700 --> 01:02:18.970
So I will entertain,
I recognize that we're

01:02:18.970 --> 01:02:21.740
four minutes over 1 o'clock.

01:02:21.740 --> 01:02:24.290
I have about 10 minutes
that I can answer questions

01:02:24.290 --> 01:02:27.770
if you have any questions
about the seven principles.

01:02:27.770 --> 01:02:29.735
And I'll stick around.

