LAURA HECK: Yeah, you bet.

01:03:29.455 --> 01:03:32.540
AUDIENCE: So perhaps except
for the licking part,

01:03:32.540 --> 01:03:35.590
are there any of those tips
or principles or guidelines

01:03:35.590 --> 01:03:38.434
not applicable to
workplace relationships?

01:03:38.434 --> 01:03:40.350
LAURA HECK: OK, so are
any of these principles

01:03:40.350 --> 01:03:42.810
not applicable to
workplace relationships?

01:03:49.415 --> 01:03:52.300
No, not a single one.

01:03:52.300 --> 01:03:53.890
They are all
directly applicable.

01:03:53.890 --> 01:03:56.050
Here's what I'll say about
workplace relationships,

01:03:56.050 --> 01:04:00.360
and I will say this specifically
between males and females,

01:04:00.360 --> 01:04:02.360
that if you have
a partner at home,

01:04:02.360 --> 01:04:05.000
you want to be comfortable or
careful about your boundaries.

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:07.564
So the information that you're
sharing with your partner

01:04:07.564 --> 01:04:09.730
is going to be different
with the information you're

01:04:09.730 --> 01:04:11.570
sharing within a workplace.

01:04:11.570 --> 01:04:14.660
This is if you have, like,
male-female workplace

01:04:14.660 --> 01:04:15.410
coworkers.

01:04:15.410 --> 01:04:18.160
But all of these are
directly applicable,

01:04:18.160 --> 01:04:22.350
so knowing your coworker, asking
them open-ended questions.

01:04:22.350 --> 01:04:24.940
It's really incredible
what can change

01:04:24.940 --> 01:04:27.910
with the dynamic of someone
that you're working with.

01:04:27.910 --> 01:04:30.250
Let's just say that you
only are coming together

01:04:30.250 --> 01:04:32.960
and all you have is
shop talk, just trying

01:04:32.960 --> 01:04:36.500
to solve problems related
to your work description.

01:04:36.500 --> 01:04:38.680
But if you happen to know
that this person really

01:04:38.680 --> 01:04:41.750
enjoys golf on the weekends
and you ask him, like,

01:04:41.750 --> 01:04:43.730
hey, did you happen to
go golfing this weekend

01:04:43.730 --> 01:04:47.160
and how are the kids or I know
that your birthday's coming up.

01:04:47.160 --> 01:04:51.990
Knowing the inner pieces,
having a Love Map for the people

01:04:51.990 --> 01:04:53.990
that you work with is important.

01:04:53.990 --> 01:04:57.320
The other part is, have you
ever noticed this is the repair

01:04:57.320 --> 01:05:00.190
part, maybe you
said something that

01:05:00.190 --> 01:05:06.520
might have been misconstrued
or perhaps made your coworker

01:05:06.520 --> 01:05:07.970
upset in some way.

01:05:07.970 --> 01:05:10.330
You can use a repair to
get you back on track.

01:05:10.330 --> 01:05:12.890
So all of these are
directly applicable.

01:05:12.890 --> 01:05:14.220
Yeah.

01:05:14.220 --> 01:05:16.300
There isn't research
that's been done

01:05:16.300 --> 01:05:19.260
yet by Dr. Gottman on
that relationship, only

01:05:19.260 --> 01:05:20.870
on intimate
relationships, but there

01:05:20.870 --> 01:05:23.740
is a program that's being
developed for coworkers

01:05:23.740 --> 01:05:25.910
in a professional setting.

01:05:25.910 --> 01:05:28.864
Any other questions?

01:05:28.864 --> 01:05:29.363
Yeah?

01:05:32.820 --> 01:05:34.680
AUDIENCE: Maybe you have advice.

01:05:34.680 --> 01:05:38.150
How to complain without
criticism, I think,

01:05:38.150 --> 01:05:40.050
is the way you phrased it.

01:05:40.050 --> 01:05:44.340
How do you complain,
I see how it's better

01:05:44.340 --> 01:05:48.270
to describe how you're
feeling and what bothers you

01:05:48.270 --> 01:05:50.090
instead of just saying
you always do this.

01:05:50.090 --> 01:05:50.920
LAURA HECK: Right.

01:05:50.920 --> 01:05:52.870
AUDIENCE: But even
that can sound

01:05:52.870 --> 01:05:54.470
passive aggressive and whiny.

01:05:54.470 --> 01:05:56.950
If you just use the
words the other way,

01:05:56.950 --> 01:05:59.270
it can still come
across as an attack.

01:05:59.270 --> 01:06:04.970
So how do you actually practice
communicating instead of just

01:06:04.970 --> 01:06:06.830
attacking passive aggressively?

01:06:06.830 --> 01:06:07.500
LAURA HECK: OK.

01:06:07.500 --> 01:06:10.070
So if you're using
like an I statement.

01:06:10.070 --> 01:06:12.960
So passive aggressive.

01:06:12.960 --> 01:06:14.650
So part of the passive
aggressive piece

01:06:14.650 --> 01:06:17.110
is when people don't take
ownership for something,

01:06:17.110 --> 01:06:20.400
and what we're really asking
is that you're taking ownership

01:06:20.400 --> 01:06:21.740
of what's bothering you.

01:06:21.740 --> 01:06:22.900
And that's OK.

01:06:22.900 --> 01:06:24.930
Because when things
store up, they sort of

01:06:24.930 --> 01:06:26.510
are like a volcano.

01:06:26.510 --> 01:06:27.810
They bubble to the surface.

01:06:27.810 --> 01:06:30.350
So we're asking that people
take some ownership of something

01:06:30.350 --> 01:06:32.550
that's bothering them
and use the I statements.

01:06:32.550 --> 01:06:37.610
So I'm upset about this, I'm
frustrated, I'm hurt, I'm sad,

01:06:37.610 --> 01:06:38.890
I'm lonely.

01:06:38.890 --> 01:06:41.820
And when you take
ownership of that,

01:06:41.820 --> 01:06:44.354
it loses the passive
aggressive piece

01:06:44.354 --> 01:06:46.020
because you're really
not doing passive.

01:06:46.020 --> 01:06:47.020
You're taking ownership.

01:06:47.020 --> 01:06:49.370
You're being more assertive
in your relationship.

01:06:49.370 --> 01:06:52.010
So I'm lonely.

01:06:52.010 --> 01:06:55.920
I haven't seen you for
the last three nights.

01:06:55.920 --> 01:06:56.761
That's true, right?

01:06:56.761 --> 01:06:58.260
So you're describing
what's going on

01:06:58.260 --> 01:06:59.660
in a non-judgmental way.

01:06:59.660 --> 01:07:01.660
You're simply stating
what's going on.

01:07:01.660 --> 01:07:05.110
I haven't seen you for the
last three nights, I'm lonely.

01:07:05.110 --> 01:07:08.610
I'd really like it if we could
schedule a date night sometime

01:07:08.610 --> 01:07:10.920
this week so that
we can reconnect.

01:07:10.920 --> 01:07:14.410
Or I was really hurt when
you didn't introduce me

01:07:14.410 --> 01:07:16.612
to your boss this afternoon.

01:07:16.612 --> 01:07:19.440
I really would love to get to
know the people in your life

01:07:19.440 --> 01:07:21.240
that you're spending
most of your day with.

01:07:21.240 --> 01:07:24.680
Do you mind if maybe we could
go out for dinner with him

01:07:24.680 --> 01:07:26.660
and his wife sometime next week?

01:07:26.660 --> 01:07:27.992
Whatever it might be.

01:07:27.992 --> 01:07:29.700
I don't know if I
answered your question,

01:07:29.700 --> 01:07:33.490
but part of the piece
about complaining

01:07:33.490 --> 01:07:37.560
is that I'm not saying that
it's not going to-- nobody

01:07:37.560 --> 01:07:39.137
likes to complain, right?

01:07:39.137 --> 01:07:41.720
You don't like to complain, you
don't like to hear complaints,

01:07:41.720 --> 01:07:44.840
but what we're trying
to do is that we're

01:07:44.840 --> 01:07:48.100
trying to change the complaints
so that the criticism.

01:07:48.100 --> 01:07:50.650
So they're not criticizing
your partner in a global way.

01:07:50.650 --> 01:07:53.401
You're certainly going to
complain about this one thing

01:07:53.401 --> 01:07:55.650
right here and you're not
going to store it up, rather

01:07:55.650 --> 01:07:58.030
than globalizing it and
criticizing your partner

01:07:58.030 --> 01:08:00.210
altogether.

01:08:00.210 --> 01:08:03.400
Any other questions?

01:08:03.400 --> 01:08:03.900
No?

01:08:03.900 --> 01:08:08.270
OK, I hope you guys enjoy
the rest of your work day.

